[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] One major practical drawback is its $O(b^{d})$ space complexity where d is the depth of the shallowest solution (the length of the shortest path from the source node to any given goal node) and b is the branching factor (the maximum number of successors for any given state).
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] In practical travel-routing systems, it is generally outperformed by algorithms that can pre-process the graph to attain better performance, as well as by memory-bounded approaches; however, A* is still the best solution in many cases.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] Peter Hart, Nils Nilsson and Bertram Raphael of Stanford Research Institute (now SRI International) first published the algorithm in 1968.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] It can be seen as an extension of Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] A* achieves better performance by using heuristics to guide its search.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] The A* algorithm terminates once it finds the shortest path to a specified goal, rather than generating the entire shortest-path tree from a specified source to all possible goals.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] A* was created as part of the Shakey project, which had the aim of building a mobile robot that could plan its own actions.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] Nils Nilsson originally proposed using the Graph Traverser algorithm for Shakey's path planning.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] Graph Traverser is guided by a heuristic function *h*(*n*), the estimated distance from node n to the goal node: it entirely ignores *g*(*n*), the distance from the start node to n.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] Bertram Raphael suggested using the sum, *g*(*n*) + *h*(*n*).
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] Peter Hart invented the concepts we now call admissibility and consistency of heuristic functions.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] A* was originally designed for finding least-cost paths when the cost of a path is the sum of its costs, but it has been shown that A* can be used to find optimal paths for any problem satisfying the conditions of a cost algebra.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] The original 1968 A* paper contained a theorem stating that no A*-like algorithm could expand fewer nodes than A* if the heuristic function is consistent and A*'s tie-breaking rule is suitably chosen.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] A* is an informed search algorithm, or a best-first search, meaning that it is formulated in terms of weighted graphs: starting from a specific starting node of a graph, it aims to find a path to the given goal node having the smallest cost (least distance travelled, shortest time, etc.).
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] It does this by maintaining a tree of paths originating at the start node and extending those paths one edge at a time until the goal node is reached.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] At each iteration of its main loop, A* needs to determine which of its paths to extend.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] It does so based on the cost of the path and an estimate of the cost required to extend the path all the way to the goal.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] where n is the next node on the path, *g*(*n*) is the cost of the path from the start node to n, and *h*(*n*) is a heuristic function that estimates the cost of the cheapest path from n to the goal.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] The heuristic function is problem-specific.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] Typical implementations of A* use a priority queue to perform the repeated selection of minimum (estimated) cost nodes to expand.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] This priority queue is known as the *open set*, *fringe* or *frontier*.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] At each step of the algorithm, the node with the lowest *f*(*x*) value is removed from the queue, the f and g values of its neighbors are updated accordingly, and these neighbors are added to the queue.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] The algorithm continues until a removed node (thus the node with the lowest f value out of all fringe nodes) is a goal node.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] The f value of that goal is then also the cost of the shortest path, since h at the goal is zero in an admissible heuristic.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] The algorithm described so far only gives the length of the shortest path.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] To find the actual sequence of steps, the algorithm can be easily revised so that each node on the path keeps track of its predecessor.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] After this algorithm is run, the ending node will point to its predecessor, and so on, until some node's predecessor is the start node.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] As an example, when searching for the shortest route on a map, *h*(*x*) might represent the straight-line distance to the goal, since that is physically the smallest possible distance between any two points.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] For a grid map from a video game, using the Taxicab distance or the Chebyshev distance becomes better depending on the set of movements available (4-way or 8-way).
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] If the heuristic h satisfies the additional condition *h*(*x*) ≤ *d*(*x*, *y*) + *h*(*y*) for every edge (*x*, *y*) of the graph (where d denotes the length of that edge), then h is called monotone, or consistent.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] With a consistent heuristic, A* is guaranteed to find an optimal path without processing any node more than once and A* is equivalent to running Dijkstra's algorithm with the reduced cost *d'*(*x*, *y*) = *d*(*x*, *y*) + *h*(*y*) − *h*(*x*).
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] The A* algorithm has real-world applications.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] In this example, edges are railroads and h(x) is the great-circle distance (the shortest possible distance on a sphere) to the target.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] The algorithm is searching for a path between Washington, D.C., and Los Angeles.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] There are a number of simple optimizations or implementation details that can significantly affect the performance of an A* implementation.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] The first detail to note is that the way the priority queue handles ties can have a significant effect on performance in some situations.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] If ties are broken so the queue behaves in a LIFO manner, A* will behave like depth-first search among equal cost paths (avoiding exploring more than one equally optimal solution).
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] When a path is required at the end of the search, it is common to keep with each node a reference to that node's parent.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] At the end of the search, these references can be used to recover the optimal path.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] If these references are being kept then it can be important that the same node doesn't appear in the priority queue more than once (each entry corresponding to a different path to the node, and each with a different cost).
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] A standard approach here is to check if a node about to be added already appears in the priority queue.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] If it does, then the priority and parent pointers are changed to correspond to the lower-cost path.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] A standard binary heap based priority queue does not directly support the operation of searching for one of its elements, but it can be augmented with a hash table that maps elements to their position in the heap, allowing this decrease-priority operation to be performed in logarithmic time.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] Alternatively, a Fibonacci heap can perform the same decrease-priority operations in constant amortized time.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] Dijkstra's algorithm, as another example of a uniform-cost search algorithm, can be viewed as a special case of A* where ⁠ $h(x)=0$ ⁠ for all *x*.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] General depth-first search can be implemented using A* by considering that there is a global counter *C* initialized with a very large value.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] Every time we process a node we assign *C* to all of its newly discovered neighbors.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] After every single assignment, we decrease the counter *C* by one.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] Thus the earlier a node is discovered, the higher its ⁠ $h(x)$ ⁠ value.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] Both Dijkstra's algorithm and depth-first search can be implemented more efficiently without including an ⁠ $h(x)$ ⁠ value at each node.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] On finite graphs with non-negative edge weights A* is guaranteed to terminate and is *complete*, i.e. it will always find a solution (a path from start to goal) if one exists.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] On infinite graphs with a finite branching factor and edge costs that are bounded away from zero ( ${\textstyle d(x,y)>\varepsilon >0}$ for some fixed $\varepsilon$ ), A* is guaranteed to terminate only if there exists a solution.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] A search algorithm is said to be *admissible* if it is guaranteed to return an optimal solution.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] If the heuristic function used by A* is admissible, then A* is admissible.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] Call a node *closed* if it has been visited and is not in the open set.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] We *close* a node when we remove it from the open set.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] A basic property of the A* algorithm, which we'll sketch a proof of below, is that when ⁠ n ⁠ is closed, ⁠ $f(n)$ ⁠ is an optimistic estimate (lower bound) of the true distance from the start to the goal.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] So when the goal node, ⁠ g ⁠, is closed, ⁠ $f(g)$ ⁠ is no more than the true distance.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] On the other hand, it is no less than the true distance, since it is the length of a path to the goal plus a heuristic term.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] Now we'll see that whenever a node ⁠ n ⁠ is closed, ⁠ $f(n)$ ⁠ is an optimistic estimate.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] Let ⁠ P ⁠ be an optimal path from the start to the goal.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] Let ⁠ p ⁠ be the last closed node on ⁠ P ⁠ for which ⁠ $g(p)$ ⁠ is the true distance from the start to ⁠ p ⁠ (the start is one such vertex).
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] The next node in ⁠ P ⁠ has the correct ⁠ g ⁠ value, since it was updated when ⁠ p ⁠ was closed, and it is open since it is not closed.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] The definitive study of the optimal efficiency of A* is due to Rina Dechter and Judea Pearl.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] They considered a variety of definitions of **Alts** and **P** in combination with A*'s heuristic being merely admissible or being both consistent and admissible.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] The most interesting positive result they proved is that A*, with a consistent heuristic, is optimally efficient with respect to all admissible A*-like search algorithms on all "non-pathological" search problems.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] Roughly speaking, their notion of the non-pathological problem is what we now mean by "up to tie-breaking".
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] This result does not hold if A*'s heuristic is admissible but not consistent.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] In that case, Dechter and Pearl showed there exist admissible A*-like algorithms that can expand arbitrarily fewer nodes than A* on some non-pathological problems.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] Optimal efficiency is about the *set* of nodes expanded, not the *number* of node expansions (the number of iterations of A*'s main loop).
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] When the heuristic being used is admissible but not consistent, it is possible for a node to be expanded by A* many times, an exponential number of times in the worst case.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] In such circumstances, Dijkstra's algorithm could outperform A* by a large margin.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] While the admissibility criterion guarantees an optimal solution path, it also means that A* must examine all equally meritorious paths to find the optimal path.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] To compute approximate shortest paths, it is possible to speed up the search at the expense of optimality by relaxing the admissibility criterion.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] Oftentimes we want to bound this relaxation, so that we can guarantee that the solution path is no worse than (1 + *ε*) times the optimal solution path.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] This new guarantee is referred to as *ε*-admissible.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] As a heuristic search algorithm, the performance of A* is heavily influenced by the quality of the heuristic function ${\textstyle h(n)}$ .
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] If the heuristic closely approximates the true cost to the goal, A* can significantly reduce the number of node expansions.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] On the other hand, a poor heuristic can lead to many unnecessary expansions.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] In the worst case, A* expands all nodes ${\textstyle n}$ for which ${\textstyle f(n)=g(n)+h(n)\leq C^{*}}$ , where ${\textstyle C^{*}}$ is the cost of the optimal goal node.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] Suppose there is a node ${\textstyle N'}$ in the open list with ${\textstyle f(N')>C^{*}}$ , and it's the next node to be expanded.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] Since the goal node has ${\textstyle f(goal)=g(goal)+h(goal)=g(goal)=C^{*}}$ , and ${\textstyle f(N')>C^{*}}$ , the goal node will have a lower f-value and will be expanded before ${\textstyle N'}$ .
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] Therefore, A* never expands nodes with ${\textstyle f(n)>C^{*}}$ .
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] Assume there exists an optimal algorithm that expands fewer nodes than ${\textstyle C^{*}}$ in the worst case using the same heuristic.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] That means there must be some node ${\textstyle N'}$ such that ${\textstyle f(N')<C^{*}}$ , yet the algorithm chooses not to expand it.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] Now consider a modified graph where a new edge of cost ${\textstyle \varepsilon }$ (with ${\textstyle \varepsilon >0}$ ) is added from ${\textstyle N'}$ to the goal.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] If ${\textstyle f(N')+\varepsilon <C^{*}}$ , then the new optimal path goes through ${\textstyle N'}$ .
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] However, since the algorithm still avoids expanding ${\textstyle N'}$ , it will miss the new optimal path, violating its optimality.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] Therefore, no optimal algorithm including A* could expand fewer nodes than ${\textstyle C^{*}}$ in the worst case.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] The worst-case complexity of A* is often described as ${\textstyle O(b^{d})}$ , where b is the branching factor and ${\textstyle d}$ is the depth of the shallowest goal.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] While this gives a rough intuition, it does not precisely capture the actual behavior of A*.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] A more accurate bound considers the number of nodes with ${\textstyle f(n)\leq C^{*}}$ .
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] This represents both the time and space complexity in the worst case.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] The space complexity of A* is roughly the same as that of all other graph search algorithms, as it keeps all generated nodes in memory.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] In practice, this turns out to be the biggest drawback of the A* search, leading to the development of memory-bounded heuristic searches, such as Iterative deepening A*, memory-bounded A*, and SMA*.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] A* is often used for the common pathfinding problem in applications such as video games, but was originally designed as a general graph traversal algorithm.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] It finds applications in diverse problems, including the problem of parsing using stochastic grammars in NLP.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] Other cases include an Informational search with online learning.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] What sets A* apart from a greedy best-first search algorithm is that it takes the cost/distance already traveled, *g*(*n*), into account.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] Some common variants of Dijkstra's algorithm can be viewed as a special case of A* where the heuristic $h(n)=0$ for all nodes; in turn, both Dijkstra and A* are special cases of dynamic programming.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] A* itself is a special case of a generalization of branch and bound.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] A* is similar to beam search except that beam search maintains a limit on the numbers of paths that it has to explore.
[src:problem-solving/a-search-algorithm] A* can also be adapted to a bidirectional search algorithm, but special care needs to be taken for the stopping criterion.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] John McCarthy during the Dartmouth Workshop met Alex Bernstein of IBM, who was writing a chess program.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] McCarthy invented alpha–beta search and recommended it to him, but Bernstein was "unconvinced".
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] Simon who used what John McCarthy calls an "approximation" in 1958 wrote that alpha–beta "appears to have been reinvented a number of times".
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] Arthur Samuel had an early version for a checkers simulation.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] Richards, Timothy Hart, Michael Levin and/or Daniel Edwards also invented alpha–beta independently in the United States.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] McCarthy proposed similar ideas during the Dartmouth workshop in 1956 and suggested it to a group of his students including Alan Kotok at MIT in 1961.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] Alexander Brudno independently conceived the alpha–beta algorithm, publishing his results in 1963.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] Judea Pearl proved its optimality in terms of the expected running time for trees with randomly assigned leaf values in two papers.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] The optimality of the randomized version of alpha–beta was shown by Michael Saks and Avi Wigderson in 1986.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] A game tree can represent many two-player zero-sum games, such as chess, checkers, and reversi.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] Each node in the tree represents a possible situation in the game.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] Each terminal node (outcome) of a branch is assigned a numeric score that determines the value of the outcome to the player with the next move.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] The algorithm maintains two values, alpha and beta, which respectively represent the minimum score that the maximizing player is assured of and the maximum score that the minimizing player is assured of.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] Initially, alpha is negative infinity and beta is positive infinity, i.e. both players start with their worst possible score.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] To illustrate this with a real-life example, suppose somebody is playing chess, and it is their turn.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] Move "A" will improve the player's position.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] The player continues to look for moves to make sure a better one hasn't been missed.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] Move "B" is also a good move, but the player then realizes that it will allow the opponent to force checkmate in two moves.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] Thus, other outcomes from playing move B no longer need to be considered since the opponent can force a win.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] The maximum score that the opponent could force after move "B" is negative infinity: a loss for the player.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] This is less than the minimum position that was previously found; move "A" does not result in a forced loss in two moves.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] The benefit of alpha–beta pruning lies in the fact that branches of the search tree can be eliminated.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] This way, the search time can be limited to the 'more promising' subtree, and a deeper search can be performed in the same time.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] Like its predecessor, it belongs to the branch and bound class of algorithms.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] The optimization reduces the effective depth to slightly more than half that of simple minimax if the nodes are evaluated in an optimal or near optimal order (best choice for side on move ordered first at each node).
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] With an (average or constant) branching factor of *b*, and a search depth of *d* plies, the maximum number of leaf node positions evaluated (when the move ordering is pessimal) is *O*(*b**d*) – the same as a simple minimax search.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] In the latter case, where the ply of a search is even, the effective branching factor is reduced to its square root, or, equivalently, the search can go twice as deep with the same amount of computation.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] The explanation of *b*×1×*b*×1×... is that all the first player's moves must be studied to find the best one, but for each, only the second player's best move is needed to refute all but the first (and best) first player move—alpha–beta ensures no other second player moves need be considered.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] When nodes are considered in a random order (i.e., the algorithm randomizes), asymptotically, the expected number of nodes evaluated in uniform trees with binary leaf-values is $\Theta \left(\left({\frac {b-1+{\sqrt {b^{2}+14b+1}}}{4}}\right)^{d}\right)$ .
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] When the leaf values are chosen independently of each other but from the $[0,1]$ interval uniformly at random, the expected number of nodes evaluated increases to $\Theta \left(b^{d/\log(d)}\right)$ in the $d\to \infty$ limit, which is again optimal for this kind of random tree.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] Note that the actual work for "small" values of d is better approximated using $0.925d^{0.747}$ .
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] A chess program that searches four plies with an average of 36 branches per node evaluates more than one million terminal nodes.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] An optimal alpha-beta prune would eliminate all but about 2,000 terminal nodes, a reduction of 99.8%.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] This advantage can switch sides many times during the search if the move ordering is incorrect, each time leading to inefficiency.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] As the number of positions searched decreases exponentially each move nearer the current position, it is worth spending considerable effort on sorting early moves.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] An improved sort at any depth will exponentially reduce the total number of positions searched, but sorting all positions at depths near the root node is relatively cheap as there are so few of them.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] In practice, the move ordering is often determined by the results of earlier, smaller searches, such as through iterative deepening.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] Additionally, this algorithm can be trivially modified to return an entire principal variation in addition to the score.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] Some more aggressive algorithms such as MTD(f) do not easily permit such a modification.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] Implementations of alpha–beta pruning can often be delineated by whether they are "fail-soft," or "fail-hard".
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] The pseudo-code illustrates the fail-soft variation.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] With fail-soft alpha–beta, the alphabeta function may return values (v) that exceed (v < α or v > β) the α and β bounds set by its function call arguments.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] In comparison, fail-hard alpha–beta limits its function return value into the inclusive range of α and β.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] Further improvement can be achieved without sacrificing accuracy by using ordering heuristics to search earlier parts of the tree that are likely to force alpha–beta cutoffs.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] For example, in chess, moves that capture pieces may be examined before moves that do not, and moves that have scored highly in earlier passes through the game-tree analysis may be evaluated before others.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] Another common, and very cheap, heuristic is the killer heuristic, where the last move that caused a beta-cutoff at the same tree level in the tree search is always examined first.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] This idea can also be generalized into a set of refutation tables.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] Alpha–beta search can be made even faster by considering only a narrow search window (generally determined by guesswork based on experience).
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] This is known as an *aspiration window*.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] In the extreme case, the search is performed with alpha and beta equal; a technique known as *zero-window search*, *null-window search*, or *scout search*.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] This is particularly useful for win/loss searches near the end of a game where the extra depth gained from the narrow window and a simple win/loss evaluation function may lead to a conclusive result.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] If an aspiration search fails, it is straightforward to detect whether it failed *high* (high edge of window was too low) or *low* (lower edge of window was too high).
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] This gives information about what window values might be useful in a re-search of the position.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] Over time, other improvements have been suggested, and indeed the Falphabeta (fail-soft alpha–beta) idea of John Fishburn is nearly universal and is already incorporated above in a slightly modified form.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] Fishburn also suggested a combination of the killer heuristic and zero-window search under the name Lalphabeta ("last move with minimal window alpha–beta search").
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] Since the minimax algorithm and its variants are inherently depth-first, a strategy such as iterative deepening is usually used in conjunction with alpha–beta so that a reasonably good move can be returned even if the algorithm is interrupted before it has finished execution.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] Another advantage of using iterative deepening is that searches at shallower depths give move-ordering hints, as well as shallow alpha and beta estimates, that both can help produce cutoffs for higher depth searches much earlier than would otherwise be possible.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] Algorithms like SSS*, on the other hand, use the best-first strategy.
[src:problem-solving/alpha-beta-pruning] This can potentially make them more time-efficient, but typically at a heavy cost in space-efficiency.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] The classic textbook example of the use of backtracking is the eight queens puzzle, that asks for all arrangements of eight chess queens on a standard chessboard so that no queen attacks any other.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] In the common backtracking approach, the partial candidates are arrangements of *k* queens in the first *k* rows of the board, all in different rows and columns.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] Any partial solution that contains two mutually attacking queens can be abandoned.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] Backtracking can be applied only for problems which admit the concept of a "partial candidate solution" and a relatively quick test of whether it can possibly be completed to a valid solution.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] It is useless, for example, for locating a given value in an unordered table.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] When it is applicable, however, backtracking is often much faster than brute-force enumeration of all complete candidates, since it can eliminate many candidates with a single test.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] Backtracking is an important tool for solving constraint satisfaction problems, such as crosswords, verbal arithmetic, Sudoku, and many other puzzles.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] It is often the most convenient technique for parsing, for the knapsack problem and other combinatorial optimization problems.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] It is also the program execution strategy used in the programming languages Icon, Planner and Prolog.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] Backtracking depends on user-given "black box procedures" that define the problem to be solved, the nature of the partial candidates, and how they are extended into complete candidates.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] It is therefore a metaheuristic rather than a specific algorithm – although, unlike many other meta-heuristics, it is guaranteed to find all solutions to a finite problem in a bounded amount of time.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] The term "backtrack" was coined by American mathematician D.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] The pioneer string-processing language SNOBOL (1962) may have been the first to provide a built-in general backtracking facility.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] The backtracking algorithm enumerates a set of *partial candidates* that, in principle, could be *completed* in various ways to give all the possible solutions to the given problem.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] The backtracking algorithm traverses this search tree recursively, from the root down, in depth-first order.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] At each node *c*, the algorithm checks whether *c* can be completed to a valid solution.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] If it cannot, the whole sub-tree rooted at *c* is skipped (*pruned*).
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] Otherwise, the algorithm (1) checks whether *c* itself is a valid solution, and if so reports it to the user; and (2) recursively enumerates all sub-trees of *c*.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] The two tests and the children of each node are defined by user-given procedures.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] Therefore, the *actual search tree* that is traversed by the algorithm is only a part of the potential tree.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] The total cost of the algorithm is the number of nodes of the actual tree times the cost of obtaining and processing each node.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] This fact should be considered when choosing the potential search tree and implementing the pruning test.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] In order to apply backtracking to a specific class of problems, one must provide the data *P* for the particular instance of the problem that is to be solved, and six procedural parameters, *root*, *reject*, *accept*, *first*, *next*, and *output*.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] *reject*(*P*,*c*): return *true* only if the partial candidate *c* is not worth completing.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] *accept*(*P*,*c*): return *true* if *c* is a solution of *P*, and *false* otherwise.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] *first*(*P*,*c*): generate the first extension of candidate *c*.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] *next*(*P*,*s*): generate the next alternative extension of a candidate, after the extension *s*.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] *output*(*P*,*c*): use the solution *c* of *P*, as appropriate to the application.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] The *reject* procedure should be a Boolean-valued function that returns *true* only if it is certain that no possible extension of *c* is a valid solution for *P*.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] If the procedure cannot reach a definite conclusion, it should return *false*.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] An incorrect *true* result may cause the *backtrack* procedure to miss some valid solutions.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] The procedure may assume that *reject*(*P*,*t*) returned *false* for every ancestor *t* of *c* in the search tree.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] On the other hand, the efficiency of the backtracking algorithm depends on *reject* returning *true* for candidates that are as close to the root as possible.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] If *reject* always returns *false*, the algorithm will still find all solutions, but it will be equivalent to a brute-force search.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] The *accept* procedure should return *true* if *c* is a complete and valid solution for the problem instance *P*, and *false* otherwise.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] It may assume that the partial candidate *c* and all its ancestors in the tree have passed the *reject* test.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] The general pseudo-code above does not assume that the valid solutions are always leaves of the potential search tree.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] In other words, it admits the possibility that a valid solution for *P* can be further extended to yield other valid solutions.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] The *first* and *next* procedures are used by the backtracking algorithm to enumerate the children of a node *c* of the tree, that is, the candidates that differ from *c* by a single extension step.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] The call *first*(*P*,*c*) should yield the first child of *c*, in some order; and the call *next*(*P*,*s*) should return the next sibling of node *s*, in that order.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] Both functions should return a distinctive "NULL" candidate, if the requested child does not exist.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] Together, the *root*, *first*, and *next* functions define the set of partial candidates and the potential search tree.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] They should be chosen so that every solution of *P* occurs somewhere in the tree, and no partial candidate occurs more than once.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] Moreover, they should admit an efficient and effective *reject* predicate.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] The pseudo-code above will call *output* for all candidates that are a solution to the given instance *P*.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] The algorithm can be modified to stop after finding the first solution, or a specified number of solutions; or after testing a specified number of partial candidates, or after spending a given amount of CPU time.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] The general constraint satisfaction problem consists in finding a list of integers *x* = (*x*[1], *x*[2], …, *x*[*n*]), each in some range {1, 2, …, *m*}, that satisfies some arbitrary constraint (Boolean function) *F*.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] For this class of problems, the instance data *P* would be the integers *m* and *n*, and the predicate *F*.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] In a typical backtracking solution to this problem, one could define a partial candidate as a list of integers *c* = (*c*[1], *c*[2], …, *c*[k]), for any *k* between 0 and *n*, that are to be assigned to the first *k* variables *x*[1], *x*[2], …, *x*[*k*].
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] The root candidate would then be the empty list ().
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] Here *length*(*c*) is the number of elements in the list *c*.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] The call *reject*(*P*, *c*) should return *true* if the constraint *F* cannot be satisfied by any list of *n* integers that begins with the *k* elements of *c*.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] For backtracking to be effective, there must be a way to detect this situation, at least for some candidates *c*, without enumerating all those *m**n* − *k* *n*-tuples.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] In fact, *reject* needs only check those terms that do depend on *x*[*k*], since the terms that depend only on *x*[1], …, *x*[*k* − 1] will have been tested further up in the search tree.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] Assuming that *reject* is implemented as above, then *accept*(*P*, *c*) needs only check whether *c* is complete, that is, whether it has *n* elements.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] It is generally better to order the list of variables so that it begins with the most critical ones (i.e. the ones with fewest value options, or which have a greater impact on subsequent choices).
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] One could also allow the *next* function to choose which variable should be assigned when extending a partial candidate, based on the values of the variables already assigned by it.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] Further improvements can be obtained by the technique of constraint propagation.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] In addition to retaining minimal recovery values used in backing up, backtracking implementations commonly keep a variable trail, to record value change history.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] An efficient implementation will avoid creating a variable trail entry between two successive changes when there is no choice point, as the backtracking will erase all of the changes as a single operation.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] An alternative to the variable trail is to keep a timestamp of when the last change was made to the variable.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] The timestamp is compared to the timestamp of a choice point.
[src:problem-solving/backtracking] If the choice point has an associated time later than that of the variable, it is unnecessary to revert the variable when the choice point is backtracked, as it was changed before the choice point occurred.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] In logic and computer science, the **Boolean satisfiability problem** (sometimes called **propositional satisfiability problem** and abbreviated **SATISFIABILITY**, **SAT** or **B-SAT**) asks whether there exists an interpretation that satisfies a given Boolean formula.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] In other words, it asks whether the formula's variables can be consistently replaced by the values TRUE or FALSE to make the formula evaluate to TRUE.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] If this is the case, the formula is called *satisfiable*, else *unsatisfiable*.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] For example, the formula "*a* AND NOT *b*" is satisfiable because one can find the values *a* = TRUE and *b* = FALSE, which make (*a* AND NOT *b*) = TRUE.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] In contrast, "*a* AND NOT *a*" is unsatisfiable.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] SAT is the first problem that was proven to be NP-complete—this is the Cook–Levin theorem.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] This means that all problems in the complexity class NP, which includes a wide range of natural decision and optimization problems, are at most as difficult to solve as SAT.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] There is no known algorithm that efficiently solves each SAT problem (where "efficiently" means "deterministically in polynomial time").
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Although such an algorithm is generally believed not to exist, this belief has not been proven or disproven mathematically.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Resolving the question of whether SAT has a polynomial-time algorithm would settle the P versus NP problem - one of the most important open problems in the theory of computing.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Nevertheless, heuristic SAT-algorithms are able to solve problem instances involving tens of thousands of variables and formulas consisting of millions of symbols, which is sufficient for many practical SAT problems occurring in artificial intelligence, circuit design, and automatic theorem proving.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] A *propositional logic formula*, also called *Boolean expression*, is built from variables, operators AND (conjunction, also denoted by ∧), OR (disjunction, ∨), NOT (negation, ¬), and parentheses.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] A formula is said to be *satisfiable* if it can be made TRUE by assigning appropriate logical values (i.e.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] The *Boolean satisfiability problem* (SAT) is, given a formula, to check whether it is satisfiable.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] This decision problem is of central importance in many areas of computer science, including theoretical computer science, complexity theory, algorithmics, cryptography and artificial intelligence.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] A *literal* is either a variable (in which case it is called a *positive literal*) or the negation of a variable (called a *negative literal*).
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] A *clause* is a disjunction of literals (or a single literal).
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] A clause is called a *Horn clause* if it contains at most one positive literal.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] A formula is in *conjunctive normal form* (CNF) if it is a conjunction of clauses (or a single clause).
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] For example, *x*1 is a positive literal, ¬*x*2 is a negative literal, and *x*1 ∨ ¬*x*2 is a clause.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] The formula (*x*1 ∨ ¬*x*2) ∧ (¬*x*1 ∨ *x*2 ∨ *x*3) ∧ ¬*x*1 is in conjunctive normal form; its first and third clauses are Horn clauses, but its second clause is not.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] The formula is satisfiable, by choosing *x*1 = FALSE, *x*2 = FALSE, and *x*3 arbitrarily, since (FALSE ∨ ¬FALSE) ∧ (¬FALSE ∨ FALSE ∨ *x*3) ∧ ¬FALSE evaluates to (FALSE ∨ TRUE) ∧ (TRUE ∨ FALSE ∨ *x*3) ∧ TRUE, and in turn to TRUE ∧ TRUE ∧ TRUE (i.e. to TRUE).
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] In contrast, the CNF formula *a* ∧ ¬*a*, consisting of two clauses of one literal, is unsatisfiable, since for *a*=TRUE or *a*=FALSE it evaluates to TRUE ∧ ¬TRUE (i.e., FALSE) or FALSE ∧ ¬FALSE (i.e., again FALSE), respectively.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] For some versions of the SAT problem, it is useful to define the notion of a *generalized conjunctive normal form* formula, viz. as a conjunction of arbitrarily many *generalized clauses*, the latter being of the form *R*(*l*1,...,*l**n*) for some Boolean function *R* and (ordinary) literals *l**i*.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Different sets of allowed Boolean functions lead to different problem versions.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] This formula is used below, with *R* being the ternary operator that is TRUE just when exactly one of its arguments is.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Using the laws of Boolean algebra, every propositional logic formula can be transformed into an equivalent conjunctive normal form, which may, however, be exponentially longer.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] while the former is a disjunction of *n* conjunctions of 2 variables, the latter consists of 2*n* clauses of *n* variables.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] However, with use of the Tseytin transformation, we may find an equisatisfiable conjunctive normal form formula with length linear in the size of the original propositional logic formula.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] SAT was the first problem known to be NP-complete, as proved by Stephen Cook at the University of Toronto in 1971 and independently by Leonid Levin at the Russian Academy of Sciences in 1973.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Until that time, the concept of an NP-complete problem did not even exist.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] The proof shows how every decision problem in the complexity class NP can be reduced to the SAT problem for CNF formulas, sometimes called **CNFSAT**.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] A useful property of Cook's reduction is that it preserves the number of accepting answers.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] For example, deciding whether a given graph has a 3-coloring is another problem in NP; if a graph has 17 valid 3-colorings, then the SAT formula produced by the Cook–Levin reduction will have 17 satisfying assignments.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] NP-completeness only refers to the run-time of the worst case instances.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Many of the instances that occur in practical applications can be solved much more quickly.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Like the satisfiability problem for arbitrary formulas, determining the satisfiability of a formula in conjunctive normal form where each clause is limited to at most three literals is NP-complete also; this problem is called **3-SAT**, **3CNFSAT**, or **3-satisfiability**.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] where *x*2, ⋯ , *x**n*−2 are fresh variables not occurring elsewhere.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Although the two formulas are not logically equivalent, they are equisatisfiable.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] The formula resulting from transforming all clauses is at most 3 times as long as its original; that is, the length growth is polynomial.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] 3-SAT is one of Karp's 21 NP-complete problems, and it is used as a starting point for proving that other problems are also NP-hard.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] This is done by polynomial-time reduction from 3-SAT to the other problem.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] An example of a problem where this method has been used is the clique problem: given a CNF formula consisting of *c* clauses, the corresponding graph consists of a vertex for each literal, and an edge between each two non-contradicting literals from different clauses; see the picture.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] The graph has a *c*-clique if and only if the formula is satisfiable.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] There is a simple randomized algorithm due to Schöning (1999) that runs in time (4/3)*n* where *n* is the number of variables in the 3-SAT proposition, and succeeds with high probability to correctly decide 3-SAT.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] The exponential time hypothesis asserts that no algorithm can solve 3-SAT (or indeed *k*-SAT for any *k* > 2) in exp(*o*(*n*)) time (that is, fundamentally faster than exponential in *n*).
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Selman, Mitchell, and Levesque (1996) give empirical data on the difficulty of randomly generated 3-SAT formulas, depending on their size parameters.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Difficulty is measured in number recursive calls made by a DPLL algorithm.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] They identified a phase transition region from almost-certainly-satisfiable to almost-certainly-unsatisfiable formulas at the clauses-to-variables ratio at about 4.26.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] 3-satisfiability can be generalized to **k-satisfiability** (**k-SAT**, also **k-CNF-SAT**), when formulas in CNF are considered with each clause containing up to k literals.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] However, since for any *k* ≥ 3, this problem can neither be easier than 3-SAT nor harder than SAT, and the latter two are NP-complete, so must be k-SAT.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Some authors restrict k-SAT to CNF formulas with **exactly k literals**.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] This does not lead to a different complexity class either, as each clause with fewer than k literals can be padded with repeated copies of the same literals.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Satisfiability and solution space geometry of k-SAT problems with randomly generated clauses have been investigated statistically.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] As a function of the clause-to-variable ratio (also known as the density), the model exhibits various phase transitions regarding satisfiability and solution space geometry.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] For satisfiability, there exists a sharp threshold such that with high probability a solution exists if and only if the density remains below this threshold.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Well below the satisfiability threshold, the solution space also undergoes a geometric phase transition, namely that it shatters into exponentially many, well-separated clusters.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] The onset of this phase transition coincides with the known algorithmic threshold, suggesting a link between geometry and algorithmic intractability.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Conjunctive normal form (in particular with 3 literals per clause) is often considered the canonical representation for SAT formulas.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] As shown above, the general SAT problem reduces to 3-SAT, the problem of determining satisfiability for formulas in this form.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] A 3-SAT formula is *Linear SAT* (*LSAT*) if each clause (viewed as a set of literals) intersects at most one other clause, and, moreover, if two clauses intersect, then they have exactly one literal in common.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] An LSAT formula can be depicted as a set of disjoint semi-closed intervals on a line.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Deciding whether an LSAT formula is satisfiable is NP-complete.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] SAT is easier if the number of literals in a clause is limited to at most 2, in which case the problem is called **2-SAT**.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] This problem can be solved in polynomial time, and in fact is complete for the complexity class NL.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] If additionally all OR operations in literals are changed to XOR operations, then the result is called **exclusive-or 2-satisfiability**, which is a problem complete for the complexity class SL = L.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] The problem of deciding the satisfiability of a given conjunction of Horn clauses is called **Horn-satisfiability**, or **HORN-SAT**.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] It can be solved in polynomial time by a single step of the unit propagation algorithm, which produces the single minimal model of the set of Horn clauses (w.r.t. the set of literals assigned to TRUE).
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] It can be seen as P's version of the Boolean satisfiability problem.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Also, deciding the truth of quantified Horn formulas can be done in polynomial time.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Horn clauses are of interest because they are able to express implication of one variable from a set of other variables.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] A generalization of the class of Horn formulas is that of renameable-Horn formulae, which is the set of formulas that can be placed in Horn form by replacing some variables with their respective negation.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Checking the existence of such a replacement can be done in linear time; therefore, the satisfiability of such formulae is in P as it can be solved by first performing this replacement and then checking the satisfiability of the resulting Horn formula.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] SAT is trivial if the formulas are restricted to those in **disjunctive normal form**, that is, they are a disjunction of conjunctions of literals.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Such a formula is indeed satisfiable if and only if at least one of its conjunctions is satisfiable, and a conjunction is satisfiable if and only if it does not contain both *x* and NOT *x* for some variable *x*.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Furthermore, if they are restricted to being in **full disjunctive normal form**, in which every variable appears exactly once in every conjunction, they can be checked in constant time (each conjunction represents one satisfying assignment).
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] But it can take exponential time and space to convert a general SAT problem to disjunctive normal form; to obtain an example, exchange "∧" and "∨" in the above exponential blow-up example for conjunctive normal forms.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Another NP-complete variant of the 3-satisfiability problem is the **one-in-three 3-SAT** (also known variously as **1-in-3-SAT** and **exactly-1 3-SAT**).
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Given a conjunctive normal form with three literals per clause, the problem is to determine whether there exists a truth assignment to the variables so that each clause has *exactly* one TRUE literal (and thus exactly two FALSE literals).
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Another variant is the **not-all-equal 3-satisfiability** problem (also called **NAE3SAT**).
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Given a conjunctive normal form with three literals per clause, the problem is to determine if an assignment to the variables exists such that in no clause all three literals have the same truth value.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] This problem is NP-complete, too, even if no negation symbols are admitted, by Schaefer's dichotomy theorem.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Another special case is the class of problems where each clause contains XOR (i.e. exclusive or) rather than (plain) OR operators.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] This is in P, since an XOR-SAT formula can also be viewed as a system of linear equations mod 2, and can be solved in cubic time by Gaussian elimination.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] The restrictions above (CNF, 2CNF, 3CNF, Horn, XOR-SAT) bound the considered formulae to be conjunctions of subformulas; each restriction states a specific form for all subformulas: for example, only binary clauses can be subformulas in 2CNF.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Schaefer's dichotomy theorem states that, for any restriction to Boolean functions that can be used to form these subformulas, the corresponding satisfiability problem is in P or NP-complete.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] The membership in P of the satisfiability of 2CNF, Horn, and XOR-SAT formulae are special cases of this theorem.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] The following table summarizes some common variants of SAT.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] An extension that has gained significant popularity since 2003 is **satisfiability modulo theories** (**SMT**) that can enrich CNF formulas with linear constraints, arrays, all-different constraints, uninterpreted functions, etc.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Such extensions typically remain NP-complete, but very efficient solvers are now available that can handle many such kinds of constraints.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] The satisfiability problem becomes more difficult if both "for all" (∀) and "there exists" (∃) quantifiers are allowed to bind the Boolean variables.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] An example of such an expression would be ∀*x* ∀*y* ∃*z* (*x* ∨ *y* ∨ *z*) ∧ (¬*x* ∨ ¬*y* ∨ ¬*z*); it is valid, since for all values of *x* and *y*, an appropriate value of *z* can be found, viz.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] *z*=TRUE if both *x* and *y* are FALSE, and *z*=FALSE else.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] SAT itself (tacitly) uses only ∃ quantifiers.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] If only ∀ quantifiers are allowed instead, the so-called **tautology problem** is obtained, which is co-NP-complete.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] If any number of both quantifiers are allowed, the problem is called the **quantified Boolean formula problem** (**QBF**), which can be shown to be PSPACE-complete.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] It is widely believed that PSPACE-complete problems are strictly harder than any problem in NP, although this has not yet been proved.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Ordinary SAT asks if there is at least one variable assignment that makes the formula true.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Other generalizations include satisfiability for first- and second-order logic, constraint satisfaction problems, 0-1 integer programming.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] While SAT is a decision problem, the search problem of finding a satisfying assignment reduces to SAT.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] That is, each algorithm which correctly answers whether an instance of SAT is solvable can be used to find a satisfying assignment.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] First, the question is asked on the given formula Φ.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] If the answer is "no", the formula is unsatisfiable.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Otherwise, the question is asked on the partly instantiated formula Φ{*x*1=TRUE}, that is, Φ with the first variable *x*1 replaced by TRUE, and simplified accordingly.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] If the answer is "yes", then *x*1=TRUE, otherwise *x*1=FALSE.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Values of other variables can be found subsequently in the same way.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] In total, *n*+1 runs of the algorithm are required, where *n* is the number of distinct variables in Φ.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Since the SAT problem is NP-complete, only algorithms with exponential worst-case complexity are known for it.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] In spite of this, efficient and scalable algorithms for SAT were developed during the 2000s and have contributed to dramatic advances in the ability to automatically solve problem instances involving tens of thousands of variables and millions of constraints (i.e. clauses).
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Examples of such problems in electronic design automation (EDA) include formal equivalence checking, model checking, formal verification of pipelined microprocessors, automatic test pattern generation, routing of FPGAs, planning, and scheduling problems, and so on.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] A SAT-solving engine is also considered to be an essential component in the electronic design automation toolbox.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Major techniques used by modern SAT solvers include the Davis–Putnam–Logemann–Loveland algorithm (or DPLL), conflict-driven clause learning (CDCL), and stochastic local search algorithms such as WalkSAT.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Almost all SAT solvers include time-outs, so they will terminate in reasonable time even if they cannot find a solution.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Different SAT solvers will find different instances easy or hard, and some excel at proving unsatisfiability, and others at finding solutions.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Recent attempts have been made to learn an instance's satisfiability using deep learning techniques.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] SAT solvers are developed and compared in SAT-solving contests.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Modern SAT solvers are also having significant impact on the fields of software verification, constraint solving in artificial intelligence, and operations research, among others.
[src:problem-solving/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Earlier runtime guarantees are shown in the diagram.
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] It is an algorithm design paradigm for discrete and combinatorial optimization problems, as well as mathematical optimization.
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] A branch-and-bound algorithm consists of a systematic enumeration of candidate solutions by means of state-space search: the set of candidate solutions is thought of as forming a rooted tree with the full set at the root.
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] The algorithm explores *branches* of this tree, which represent subsets of the solution set.
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] Before enumerating the candidate solutions of a branch, the branch is checked against upper and lower estimated *bounds* on the optimal solution, and is discarded if it cannot produce a better solution than the best one found so far by the algorithm.
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] The algorithm depends on efficient estimation of the lower and upper bounds of regions/branches of the search space.
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] If no bounds are available, then the algorithm degenerates to an exhaustive search.
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] The method was first proposed by Ailsa Land and Alison Doig whilst carrying out research at the London School of Economics sponsored by British Petroleum in 1960 for discrete programming, and has become the most commonly used tool for solving NP-hard optimization problems.
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] The name "branch and bound" first occurred in the work of Little *et al.* on the traveling salesman problem.
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] The goal of a branch-and-bound algorithm is to find a value x that maximizes or minimizes the value of a real-valued function *f*(*x*), called an objective function, among some set S of admissible or candidate solutions.
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] The set S is called the search space, or feasible region.
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] The rest of this section assumes that minimization of *f*(*x*) is desired; this assumption comes without loss of generality, since one can find the maximum value of *f*(*x*) by finding the minimum of *g*(*x*) = −*f*(*x*).
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] Turning these principles into a concrete algorithm for a specific optimization problem requires some kind of data structure that represents sets of candidate solutions.
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] Such a representation is called an *instance* of the problem.
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] Denote the set of candidate solutions of an instance I by SI.
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] Using these operations, a B&B algorithm performs a top-down recursive search through the tree of instances formed by the branch operation.
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] Upon visiting an instance I, it checks whether bound(*I*) is equal to or greater than the current upper bound; if so, I may be safely discarded from the search and the recursion stops.
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] This pruning step is usually implemented by maintaining a global variable that records the minimum upper bound seen among all instances examined so far.
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] The following is the skeleton of a generic branch-and-bound algorithm for minimizing an arbitrary objective function f.
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] To obtain an actual algorithm from this, one requires a bounding function bound, that computes lower bounds of f on nodes of the search tree, as well as a problem-specific branching rule.
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] As such, the generic algorithm presented here is a higher-order function.
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] Initialize a queue to hold a partial solution with none of the variables of the problem assigned.
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] If N represents a single candidate solution x and *f*(*x*) < *B*, then x is the best solution so far.
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] Else, *branch* on N to produce new nodes Ni.
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] Several different queue data structures can be used.
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] This FIFO-queue-based implementation yields a breadth-first search.
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] A stack (LIFO queue) will yield a depth-first algorithm.
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] A best-first branch-and-bound algorithm can be obtained by using a priority queue that sorts nodes on their lower bounds.
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] Examples of best-first search algorithms with this premise are Dijkstra's algorithm and its descendant A* search.
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] The depth-first variant is recommended when no good heuristic is available for producing an initial solution, because it quickly produces full solutions, and therefore upper bounds.
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] In the above pseudocode, the functions `heuristic_solve` and `populate_candidates` called as subroutines must be provided as applicable to the problem.
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] The functions *f* (`objective_function`) and bound (`lower_bound_function`) are treated as function objects as written, and could correspond to lambda expressions, function pointers, and other types of callable objects in the C++ programming language.
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] When $\mathbf {x}$ is a vector of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ , branch-and-bound algorithms can be combined with interval analysis and contractor techniques to provide guaranteed enclosures of the global minimum.
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] Branch-and-bound may also be a base of various heuristics.
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] For example, one may wish to stop branching when the gap between the upper and lower bounds becomes smaller than a certain threshold.
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] This is used when the solution is "good enough for practical purposes" and can greatly reduce the computations required.
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] This type of solution is particularly applicable when the cost function used is *noisy* or is the result of statistical estimates and so is not known precisely but rather only known to lie within a range of values with a specific probability.
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] Nau *et al.* present a generalization of branch and bound that also subsumes the A*, B* and alpha-beta search algorithms.
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] The first step is to relax the integer constraint.
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] We have two extreme points for the first equation that form a line: ${\begin{bmatrix}x_{1}\\x_{2}\end{bmatrix}}={\begin{bmatrix}50\\0\end{bmatrix}}$ and ${\begin{bmatrix}0\\50\end{bmatrix}}$ .
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] We can form the second line with the vector points ${\begin{bmatrix}0\\40\end{bmatrix}}$ and ${\begin{bmatrix}70\\0\end{bmatrix}}$ .
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] The third point is ${\begin{bmatrix}0\\0\end{bmatrix}}$ .
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] This is a convex hull region, so the solution lies on one of the vertices of the region.
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] We can find the intersection using row reduction, which is ${\begin{bmatrix}70/3\\80/3\end{bmatrix}}$ with a value of 276 + 2/3.
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] We test the other endpoints by sweeping the line over the region and find this is the maximum over the reals.
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] We choose the variable with the maximum fractional part, in this case $x_{2}$ becomes the parameter for the branch and bound method.
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] We have reached an integer solution so we move to the other branch $x_{2}\geq 27$ .
[src:problem-solving/branch-and-bound] We try the other branch $x_{1}\geq 23$ and there are no feasible solutions.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] The history of computational thinking as a concept dates back at least to the 1950s but most ideas are much older.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] Computational thinking involves ideas like abstraction, data representation, and logically organizing data, which are also prevalent in other kinds of thinking, such as scientific thinking, engineering thinking, systems thinking, design thinking, model-based thinking, and the like.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] Computational thinking can be used to algorithmically solve complicated problems of scale, and is often used to realize large improvements in efficiency.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] The phrase *computational thinking* was brought to the forefront of the computer science education community in 2006 as a result of a *Communications of the ACM* essay on the subject by Jeannette Wing.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] The essay suggests that thinking computationally is a fundamental skill for everyone, not just computer scientists, and argues for the importance of integrating computational ideas into other subjects in school.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] The essay also states that by learning computational thinking, children will be better in many everyday tasks; as examples, the essay gives packing one's backpack, finding one's lost mittens, and knowing when to stop renting and buying instead.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] The continuum of computational thinking questions in education ranges from K–9 computing for children to professional and continuing education, where the challenge is how to communicate deep principles, maxims, and ways of thinking between experts.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] For the first ten years computational thinking was a US-centered movement, and still today that early focus is seen in the field's research.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] The field's most cited articles and most cited people were active in the early US CT wave, and the field's most active researcher networks are US-based.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] Dominated by US and European researchers, it is unclear to what extent can the field's predominantly Western body of research literature cater to the needs of students in other cultural groups.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] The characteristics that define computational thinking are decomposition, pattern recognition / data representation, generalization/abstraction, and algorithms.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] By decomposing a problem, identifying the variables involved using data representation, and creating algorithms, a generic solution results.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] The generic solution is a generalization or abstraction that can be used to solve a multitude of variations of the initial problem.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] *Analysis*: Solution execution and evaluation.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] The four Cs of 21st-century learning are communication, critical thinking, collaboration, and creativity.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] The fifth C could be computational thinking which entails the capability to resolve problems algorithmically and logically.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] It includes tools that produce models and visualize data.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] Grover describes how computational thinking is applicable across subjects beyond science, technology, engineering, and mathematics (STEM) which include the social sciences and language arts.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] Since its inception, the 4 Cs have gradually gained acceptance as important elements of many school syllabi.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] This development triggered modifications in platforms and directions such as inquiry, project-based, and more profound learning across all K–12 levels.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] Many countries have introduced computational thinking to all students: The United Kingdom has had CT in its national curriculum since 2012.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] Singapore calls CT "national capability".
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] Other nations like Australia, China, Korea, and New Zealand have embarked on massive efforts to introduce computational thinking in schools.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] In the United States, President Barack Obama created the "Computer Science for All" program to empower a new generation of students in America with the proper computer science proficiency required to flourish in a digital economy.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] Computational thinking means thinking or solving problems like computer scientists.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] CT refers to thought processes required in understanding problems and formulating solutions.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] CT involves logic, assessment, patterns, automation, and generalization.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] Career readiness can be integrated into academic environments in multiple ways.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] The "algoRithms" part of CT has also been referred to as the "fourth R", where the others are Reading, wRiting, and aRithmetic.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] Similar to Seymour Papert, Alan Perlis, and Marvin Minsky before, Jeannette Wing envisioned computational thinking becoming an essential part of every child's education.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] Current integration of computational thinking into the K–12 curriculum comes in two forms: in computer science classes directly or through the use and measure of computational thinking techniques in other subjects.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] Teachers in Science, Technology, Engineering, and Mathematics (STEM) focused classrooms that include computational thinking, allow students to practice problem-solving skills such as trial and error.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] Valerie Barr and Chris Stephenson describe computational thinking patterns across disciplines in a 2011 ACM Inroads article However Conrad Wolfram has argued that computational thinking should be taught as a distinct subject.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] There are online institutions that provide a curriculum, and other related resources, to build and strengthen pre-college students with computational thinking, analysis and problem-solving.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] Carnegie Mellon University in Pittsburgh has a Center for Computational Thinking.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] The Center's major activity is conducting PROBEs or PROBlem-oriented Explorations.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] These PROBEs are experiments that apply novel computing concepts to problems to show the value of computational thinking.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] A PROBE experiment is generally a collaboration between a computer scientist and an expert in the field to be studied.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] The experiment typically runs for a year.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] In general, a PROBE will seek to find a solution for a broadly applicable problem and avoid narrowly focused issues.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] Some examples of PROBE experiments are optimal kidney transplant logistics and how to create drugs that do not breed drug-resistant viruses.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] The concept of computational thinking has been criticized as too vague, as it's rarely made clear how it is different from other forms of thought.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] The inclination among computer scientists to force computational solutions upon other fields has been called "computational chauvinism".
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] Some computer scientists worry about the promotion of computational thinking as a substitute for a broader computer science education, as computational thinking represents just one small part of the field.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] Others worry that the emphasis on computational thinking encourages computer scientists to think too narrowly about the problems they can solve, thus avoiding the social, ethical and environmental implications of the technology they create.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] In addition, as nearly all CT research is done in the US and Europe, it is not certain how well those educational ideas work in other cultural contexts.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] A 2019 paper argues that the term "computational thinking" (CT) should be used mainly as a shorthand to convey the educational value of computer science, hence the need of teaching it in school.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] The strategic goal is to have computer science recognized in school as an autonomous scientific subject more than trying to identify "body of knowledge" or "assessment methods" for CT.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] Particularly important is to stress the fact that the scientific novelty associated with CT is the shift from the "problem solving" of mathematics to the "having problem solved" of computer science.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] Without the "effective agent", who automatically executes the instructions received to solve the problem, there would be no computer science, but just mathematics.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] Another criticism in the same paper is that focusing on "problem solving" is too narrow, since "solving a problem is just an instance of a situation where one wants to reach a specified goal".
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] Many definitions of CT describe it only at skill level because the momentum behind its growth comes from its promise to boost STEM education.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] And, the latest movement in STEM education is based on suggestions (by learning theories) that we teach students experts' habits of mind.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] Only when we link the experts' habits of mind to fundamental cognitive processes can we then narrow their skill-sets down to more basic competencies that can be taught to novices.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] There have been only a few studies that actually address the cognitive essence of CT.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] Among those, Yasar (Communications of ACM, Vol.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] 7, July 2018) describes CT as thinking that is generated/facilitated by a computational device, be it biological or electronic.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] Accordingly, everyone employs CT, not just computer scientists, and it can be improved via education and experience.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] Computational logic is an approach to computing that includes both computational thinking and logical thinking.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] It is based on a view of computing as the application of general-purpose logical reasoning to domain-specific knowledge expressed in logical terms.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] Teaching materials for computational logic as a computer language for children were developed in the early 1980s.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] University level texts for non-computing students were developed in the early 2010s.
[src:problem-solving/computational-thinking] More recently, a variety of new teaching materials have been developed to bridge the gap between STEM and non-STEM academic disciplines.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] These are often provided with tutorials of CP, ASP, Boolean SAT and SMT solvers.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] In the general case, constraint problems can be much harder, and may not be expressible in some of these simpler systems.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] "Real life" examples include automated planning, lexical disambiguation, musicology, product configuration and resource allocation.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] The existence of a solution to a CSP can be viewed as a decision problem.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] This can be decided by finding a solution, or failing to find a solution after exhaustive search (stochastic algorithms typically never reach an exhaustive conclusion, while directed searches often do, on sufficiently small problems).
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] In some cases the CSP might be known to have solutions beforehand, through some other mathematical inference process.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] Each variable $X_{i}$ can take on the values in the nonempty domain $D_{i}$ .
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] An *evaluation* of the variables is a function from a subset of variables to a particular set of values in the corresponding subset of domains.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] An evaluation v satisfies a constraint $\langle t_{j},R_{j}\rangle$ if the values assigned to the variables $t_{j}$ satisfy the relation $R_{j}$ .
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] An evaluation is *consistent* if it does not violate any of the constraints.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] An evaluation is *complete* if it includes all variables.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] An evaluation is a *solution* if it is consistent and complete; such an evaluation is said to *solve* the constraint satisfaction problem.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] Constraint satisfaction problems on finite domains are typically solved using a form of search.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] The most used techniques are variants of backtracking, constraint propagation, and local search.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] These techniques are also often combined, as in the VLNS method, and current research involves other technologies such as linear programming.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] It maintains a partial assignment of the variables.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] Initially, all variables are unassigned.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] At each step, a variable is chosen, and all possible values are assigned to it in turn.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] For each value, the consistency of the partial assignment with the constraints is checked; in case of consistency, a recursive call is performed.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] When all values have been tried, the algorithm backtracks.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] In this basic backtracking algorithm, consistency is defined as the satisfaction of all constraints whose variables are all assigned.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] Backmarking improves the efficiency of checking consistency.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] Backjumping allows saving part of the search by backtracking "more than one variable" in some cases.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] Constraint learning infers and saves new constraints that can be later used to avoid part of the search.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] Look-ahead is also often used in backtracking to attempt to foresee the effects of choosing a variable or a value, thus sometimes determining in advance when a subproblem is satisfiable or unsatisfiable.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] Constraint propagation techniques are methods used to modify a constraint satisfaction problem.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] More precisely, they are methods that enforce a form of local consistency, which are conditions related to the consistency of a group of variables and/or constraints.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] Constraint propagation has various uses.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] First, it turns a problem into one that is equivalent but is usually simpler to solve.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] Second, it may prove satisfiability or unsatisfiability of problems.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] This is not guaranteed to happen in general; however, it always happens for some forms of constraint propagation and/or for certain kinds of problems.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] The most known and used forms of local consistency are arc consistency, hyper-arc consistency, and path consistency.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] The most popular constraint propagation method is the AC-3 algorithm, which enforces arc consistency.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] Local search methods are incomplete satisfiability algorithms.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] They may find a solution of a problem, but they may fail even if the problem is satisfiable.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] They work by iteratively improving a complete assignment over the variables.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] At each step, a small number of variables are changed in value, with the overall aim of increasing the number of constraints satisfied by this assignment.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] The min-conflicts algorithm is a local search algorithm specific for CSPs and is based on that principle.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] In practice, local search appears to work well when these changes are also affected by random choices.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] An integration of search with local search has been developed, leading to hybrid algorithms.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] CSPs are also studied in computational complexity theory, finite model theory and universal algebra.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] It turned out that questions about the complexity of CSPs translate into important universal-algebraic questions about underlying algebras.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] This approach is known as the *algebraic approach* to CSPs.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] Since every computational decision problem is polynomial-time equivalent to a CSP with an infinite template, general CSPs can have arbitrary complexity.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] In particular, there are also CSPs within the class of NP-intermediate problems, whose existence was demonstrated by Ladner, under the assumption that P ≠ NP.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] However, a large class of CSPs arising from natural applications satisfy a complexity dichotomy, meaning that every CSP within that class is either in P or NP-complete.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] These CSPs thus provide one of the largest known subsets of NP which avoids NP-intermediate problems.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] A complexity dichotomy was first proven by Schaefer for Boolean CSPs, i.e.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] CSPs over a 2-element domain and where all the available relations are Boolean operators.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] This result has been generalized for various classes of CSPs, most notably for all CSPs over finite domains.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] This *finite-domain dichotomy conjecture* was first formulated by Tomás Feder and Moshe Vardi, and finally proven independently by Andrei Bulatov and Dmitriy Zhuk in 2017.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] Most classes of CSPs that are known to be tractable are those where the hypergraph of constraints has bounded treewidth, or where the constraints have arbitrary form but there exist equationally non-trivial polymorphisms of the set of constraint relations.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] An *infinite-domain dichotomy conjecture* has been formulated for all CSPs of reducts of finitely bounded homogenous structures, stating that the CSP of such a structure is in P if and only if its polymorphism clone is equationally non-trivial, and NP-hard otherwise.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] The complexity of such infinite-domain CSPs as well as of other generalisations (Valued CSPs, Quantified CSPs, Promise CSPs) is still an area of active research.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] Every CSP can also be considered as a conjunctive query containment problem.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] A similar situation exists between the functional classes FP and #P.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] By a generalization of Ladner's theorem, there are also problems in neither FP nor #P-complete as long as FP ≠ #P.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] As in the decision case, a problem in the #CSP is defined by a set of relations.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] Each problem takes a Boolean formula as input and the task is to compute the number of satisfying assignments.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] This can be further generalized by using larger domain sizes and attaching a weight to each satisfying assignment and computing the sum of these weights.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] It is known that any complex weighted #CSP problem is either in FP or #P-hard.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] The classic model of Constraint Satisfaction Problem defines a model of static, inflexible constraints.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] This rigid model is a shortcoming that makes it difficult to represent problems easily.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] Several modifications of the basic CSP definition have been proposed to adapt the model to a wide variety of problems.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] Classic CSPs treat constraints as hard, meaning that they are *imperative* (each solution must satisfy all of them) and *inflexible* (in the sense that they must be completely satisfied or else they are completely violated).
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] **Flexible CSP**s relax those assumptions, partially *relaxing* the constraints and allowing the solution to not comply with all of them.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] This is similar to preferences in preference-based planning.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] In DCSPs each constraint variable is thought of as having a separate geographic location.
[src:problem-solving/constraint-satisfaction-problem] Strong constraints are placed on information exchange between variables, requiring the use of fully distributed algorithms to solve the constraint satisfaction problem.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In computer science, **divide and conquer** is an algorithm design paradigm.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] A divide-and-conquer algorithm recursively breaks down a problem into two or more sub-problems of the same or related type, until these become simple enough to be solved directly.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The solutions to the sub-problems are then combined to give a solution to the original problem.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Designing efficient divide-and-conquer algorithms can be difficult.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] As in mathematical induction, it is often necessary to generalize the problem to make it amenable to a recursive solution.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The correctness of a divide-and-conquer algorithm is usually proved by mathematical induction, and its computational cost is often determined by solving recurrence relations.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The divide-and-conquer paradigm is often used to find an optimal solution of a problem.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Its basic idea is to decompose a given problem into two or more similar, but simpler, subproblems, to solve them in turn, and to compose their solutions to solve the given problem.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Problems of sufficient simplicity are solved directly.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For example, to sort a given list of *n* natural numbers, split it into two lists of about *n*/2 numbers each, sort each of them in turn, and interleave both results appropriately to obtain the sorted version of the given list (see the picture).
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] This approach is known as the merge sort algorithm.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The name "divide and conquer" is sometimes applied to algorithms that reduce each problem to only one sub-problem, such as the binary search algorithm for finding a record in a sorted list (or its analogue in numerical computing, the bisection algorithm for root finding).
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] These algorithms can be implemented more efficiently than general divide-and-conquer algorithms; in particular, if they use tail recursion, they can be converted into simple loops.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Under this broad definition, however, every algorithm that uses recursion or loops could be regarded as a "divide-and-conquer algorithm".
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Therefore, some authors consider that the name "divide and conquer" should be used only when each problem may generate two or more subproblems.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The name **decrease and conquer** has been proposed instead for the single-subproblem class.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Early examples of these algorithms are primarily decrease and conquer – the original problem is successively broken down into *single* subproblems, and indeed can be solved iteratively.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Binary search, a decrease-and-conquer algorithm where the subproblems are of roughly half the original size, has a long history.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] While a clear description of the algorithm on computers appeared in 1946 in an article by John Mauchly, the idea of using a sorted list of items to facilitate searching dates back at least as far as Babylonia in 200 BC.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Another ancient decrease-and-conquer algorithm is the Euclidean algorithm to compute the greatest common divisor of two numbers by reducing the numbers to smaller and smaller equivalent subproblems, which dates to several centuries BC.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] An early two-subproblem D&C algorithm that was specifically developed for computers and properly analyzed is the merge sort algorithm, invented by John von Neumann in 1945.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Another notable example is the algorithm invented by Anatolii A.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Karatsuba in 1960 that could multiply two *n*-digit numbers in $O(n^{\log _{2}3})$ operations (in Big O notation).
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] This algorithm disproved Andrey Kolmogorov's 1956 conjecture that $\Omega (n^{2})$ operations would be required for that task.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] This is related to a radix sort, described for punch-card sorting machines as early as 1929.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Divide and conquer is a powerful tool for solving conceptually difficult problems: all it requires is a way of breaking the problem into sub-problems, of solving the trivial cases, and of combining sub-problems to the original problem.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Similarly, decrease and conquer only requires reducing the problem to a single smaller problem, such as the classic Tower of Hanoi puzzle, which reduces moving a tower of height n to move a tower of height $n-1$ .
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The divide-and-conquer paradigm often helps in the discovery of efficient algorithms.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] It was the key, for example, to Karatsuba's fast multiplication method, the quicksort and mergesort algorithms, the Strassen algorithm for matrix multiplication, and fast Fourier transforms.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In all these examples, the D&C approach led to an improvement in the asymptotic cost of the solution.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For other types of divide-and-conquer approaches, running times can also be generalized.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] If, instead, the work of splitting the problem and combining the partial solutions take $cn^{2}$ time, and there are 2 subproblems where each has size ${\frac {n}{2}}$ , then the running time of the divide-and-conquer algorithm is bounded by $O(n^{2})$ .
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Divide-and-conquer algorithms are naturally adapted for execution in multi-processor machines, especially shared-memory systems where the communication of data between processors does not need to be planned in advance because distinct sub-problems can be executed on different processors.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Divide-and-conquer algorithms naturally tend to make efficient use of memory caches.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The reason is that once a sub-problem is small enough, it and all its sub-problems can, in principle, be solved within the cache, without accessing the slower main memory.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] An algorithm designed to exploit the cache in this way is called *cache-oblivious*, because it does not contain the cache size as an explicit parameter.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Moreover, D&C algorithms can be designed for important algorithms (e.g., sorting, FFTs, and matrix multiplication) to be *optimal* cache-oblivious algorithms–they use the cache in a probably optimal way, in an asymptotic sense, regardless of the cache size.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The same advantage exists with regards to other hierarchical storage systems, such as NUMA or virtual memory, as well as for multiple levels of cache: once a sub-problem is small enough, it can be solved within a given level of the hierarchy, without accessing the higher (slower) levels.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In computations with rounded arithmetic, e.g. with floating-point numbers, a divide-and-conquer algorithm may yield more accurate results than a superficially equivalent iterative method.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For example, one can add *N* numbers either by a simple loop that adds each datum to a single variable, or by a D&C algorithm called pairwise summation that breaks the data set into two halves, recursively computes the sum of each half, and then adds the two sums.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] While the second method performs the same number of additions as the first and pays the overhead of the recursive calls, it is usually more accurate.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Divide-and-conquer algorithms are naturally implemented as recursive procedures.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In that case, the partial sub-problems leading to the one currently being solved are automatically stored in the procedure call stack.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] A recursive function is a function that calls itself within its definition.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Divide-and-conquer algorithms can also be implemented by a non-recursive program that stores the partial sub-problems in some explicit data structure, such as a stack, queue, or priority queue.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] This approach allows more freedom in the choice of the sub-problem that is to be solved next, a feature that is important in some applications — e.g. in breadth-first recursion and the branch-and-bound method for function optimization.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] This approach is also the standard solution in programming languages that do not provide support for recursive procedures.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In recursive implementations of D&C algorithms, one must make sure that there is sufficient memory allocated for the recursion stack, otherwise, the execution may fail because of stack overflow.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] D&C algorithms that are time-efficient often have relatively small recursion depth.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For example, the quicksort algorithm can be implemented so that it never requires more than $\log _{2}n$ nested recursive calls to sort n items.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Stack overflow can be difficult to prevent when using recursive procedures, since many compilers treat the recursion stack as a contiguous block of memory, and some reserve a fixed amount of space for it.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In addition, compilers may store more information on the recursion stack than is strictly required, including the return address, unchanged parameters, and the procedure’s local variables.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] As a result, the likelihood of stack overflow may be reduced by limiting the number of parameters and local variables in the recursive procedure, or by replacing recursion with an explicit stack data structure.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In any recursive algorithm, there is considerable freedom in the choice of the *base cases*, the small subproblems that are solved directly in order to terminate the recursion.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Choosing the smallest or simplest possible base cases is more elegant and usually leads to simpler programs, because there are fewer cases to consider and they are easier to solve.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For example, a Fast Fourier Transform algorithm could stop the recursion when the input is a single sample, and the quicksort list-sorting algorithm could stop when the input is the empty list; in both examples, there is only one base case to consider, and it requires no processing.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] On the other hand, efficiency often improves if the recursion is stopped at relatively large base cases, and these are solved non-recursively, resulting in a hybrid algorithm.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] This strategy avoids the overhead of recursive calls that do little or no work and may also allow the use of specialized non-recursive algorithms that, for those base cases, are more efficient than explicit recursion.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] A general procedure for a simple hybrid recursive algorithm is *short-circuiting the base case*, also known as *arm's-length recursion*.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In this case, whether the next step will result in the base case is checked before the function call, avoiding an unnecessary function call.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For example, in a tree, rather than recursing to a child node and then checking whether it is null, checking null before recursing avoids half the function calls in some algorithms on binary trees.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Since a D&C algorithm eventually reduces each problem or sub-problem instance to a large number of base instances, these often dominate the overall cost of the algorithm, especially when the splitting/joining overhead is low.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Note that these considerations do not depend on whether recursion is implemented by the compiler or by an explicit stack.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Thus, for example, many library implementations of quicksort will switch to a simple loop-based insertion sort (or similar) algorithm once the number of items to be sorted is sufficiently small.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Note that, if the empty list were the only base case, sorting a list with n entries would entail maximally n quicksort calls that would do nothing but return immediately.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Increasing the base cases to lists of size 2 or less will eliminate most of those do-nothing calls, and more generally a base case larger than 2 is typically used to reduce the fraction of time spent in function-call overhead or stack manipulation.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For example, this approach is used in some efficient FFT implementations, where the base cases are unrolled implementations of divide-and-conquer FFT algorithms for a set of fixed sizes.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Source-code generation methods may be used to produce the large number of separate base cases desirable to implement this strategy efficiently.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The generalized version of this idea is known as recursion "unrolling" or "coarsening", and various techniques have been proposed for automating the procedure of enlarging the base case.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For some problems, the branched recursion may end up evaluating the same sub-problem many times over.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In such cases it may be worth identifying and saving the solutions to these overlapping subproblems, a technique which is commonly known as memoization.
[src:problem-solving/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Followed to the limit, it leads to bottom-up divide-and-conquer algorithms such as dynamic programming.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] In philosophy and science, a **first principle** is a basic proposition or assumption that cannot be deduced from any other proposition or assumption.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] First principles in philosophy are from first cause attitudes and taught by Aristotelians, and nuanced versions of first principles are referred to as postulates by Kantians.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] In mathematics and formal logic, first principles are referred to as axioms or postulates.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] In physics and other sciences, theoretical work is said to be from first principles, or *ab initio*, if it starts directly at the level of established science and does not make assumptions such as empirical model and parameter fitting.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] Physicists include counterintuitive concepts with reiteration.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] In a formal logical system—that is, a set of propositions that are consistent with one another—it is possible that some of the statements can be deduced from other statements.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] For example, in the syllogism, *"All men are mortal; Socrates is a man; Socrates is mortal"* the last claim can be deduced from the first two.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] A first principle is an axiom that cannot be deduced from any other within that system.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] The classic example is that of Euclid's *Elements*; its hundreds of geometric propositions can be deduced from a set of definitions, postulates, and primitive notions: all three types constitute first principles.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] First principles are generally treated in the realm of philosophy known as epistemology but are an important factor in any metaphysical speculation.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] In philosophy, "first principles" are often somewhat synonymous with *a priori*, datum, and axiomatic reasoning.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] In ancient Greek philosophy, a first principle from which other principles are derived is called an *arche* and later "first principle" or "element".
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] By extension, it may mean "first place", "method of government", "empire", "realm" or "authorities".
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] The concept of an *arche* was adapted from the earliest cosmogonies of Hesiod and Orphism, through the physical theories of Pre-Socratic philosophy and Plato before being formalized as a part of metaphysics by Aristotle.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] *Arche*, sometimes also transcribed as *arkhé*, is an Ancient Greek word with primary senses "beginning", "origin" or "source of action", from the beginning, or the original argument, "command".
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] The first principle or element corresponds to the "ultimate underlying substance" and "ultimate indemonstrable principle".
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] The heritage of Greek mythology already embodied the desire to articulate reality as a whole and this universalizing impulse was fundamental for the first projects of speculative theorizing.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] It appears that the order of "being" was first imaginatively visualized before it was abstractly thought.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] In the mythological cosmogonies of the Near East, the universe is formless and empty and the only existing thing prior to creation was the water abyss.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] In the Babylonian creation story, Enuma Elish, the primordial world is described as a "watery chaos" from which everything else appeared.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] This watery chaos has similarities in the cosmogony of the Greek mythographer Pherecydes of Syros.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] In the mythical Greek cosmogony of Hesiod (8th to 7th century BC), the origin of the world is Chaos, considered as a divine primordial condition, from which everything else appeared.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] In the creation "chaos" is a gaping-void, but later the word is used to describe the space between the Earth and the sky, after their separation.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] "Chaos" may mean infinite space, or a formless matter which can be differentiated.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] The notion of temporal infinity was familiar to the Greek mind from remote antiquity in the religious conception of immortality.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] The conception of the "divine" as an origin influenced the first Greek philosophers.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] In the Orphic cosmogony, the unaging Chronos produced Aether and Chaos and made in divine Aether a silvery egg, from which everything else appeared.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] This is considered as a permanent substance or either one or more which is conserved in the generation of rest of it.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] From this all things first come to be and into this they are resolved in a final state.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] This source of entity is always preserved.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] Thales of Miletus (7th to 6th century BC), known as "the father of philosophy", claimed that the first principle of all things is water, and considered it as a substance that contains in it motion and change.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] His theory was supported by the observation of moisture throughout the world and coincided with his theory that the Earth floated on water.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] His ideas were influenced by the Near-Eastern mythological cosmogony and probably by the Homeric statement that the surrounding Oceanus (ocean) is the source of all springs and rivers.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] Anaximander argued that water could not be the arche, because it could not give rise to its opposite, fire.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] Anaximander claimed that none of the elements (earth, fire, air, water) could be arche for the same reason.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] Instead, he proposed the existence of the apeiron, an indefinite substance from which all things are born and to which all things will return.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] *Apeiron* (endless or boundless) is something completely indefinite; and Anaximander was probably influenced by the original *chaos* of Hesiod (yawning abyss).
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] Anaximander was the first philosopher to use *arche* for that which writers from Aristotle onwards called "the substratum" (Simplicius Phys.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] He probably intended it to mean primarily "indefinite in kind" but assumed it also to be "of unlimited extent and duration".
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] The notion of temporal infinity was familiar to the Greek mind from remote antiquity in the religious conception of immortality and Anaximander's description was in terms appropriate to this conception.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] This *arche* is called "eternal and ageless".
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] Anaximenes, Anaximander's pupil, advanced yet another theory.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] He returns to the elemental theory, but this time posits air, rather than water, as the arche and ascribes to it divine attributes.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] He was the first recorded philosopher who provided a theory of change and supported it with observation.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] Using two contrary processes of rarefaction and condensation (thinning or thickening), he explains how air is part of a series of changes.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] Rarefied air becomes fire, condensed it becomes first wind, then cloud, water, earth, and stone in order.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] The *arche* is technically what underlies all of reality/appearances.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] Aristotle himself calls the law of noncontradiction "the most certain of all principles" in *Metaphysics* Book IV.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] Profoundly influenced by Euclid, Descartes was a rationalist who invented the foundationalist system of philosophy.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] He used the *method of doubt*, now called Cartesian doubt, to systematically doubt everything he could possibly doubt until he was left with what he saw as purely indubitable truths.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] Using these self-evident propositions as his axioms, or foundations, he went on to deduce his entire body of knowledge from them.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] The foundations are also called *a priori* truths.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] In physics, a calculation is said to be *from first principles*, or *ab initio*, if it starts directly at the level of established laws of physics and does not make assumptions such as empirical model and fitting parameters.
[src:problem-solving/first-principle] For example, calculation of electronic structure using the Schrödinger equation within a set of approximations that do not include fitting the model to experimental data is an *ab initio* approach.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] A **genetic algorithm** (**GA**) is a metaheuristic inspired by the process of natural selection that belongs to the larger class of evolutionary algorithms (EA) in computer science and operations research.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Genetic algorithms are commonly used to generate high-quality solutions to optimization and search problems via biologically inspired operators such as selection, crossover, and mutation.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Some examples of GA applications include optimizing decision trees for better performance, solving sudoku puzzles, hyperparameter optimization, and causal inference.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] In a genetic algorithm, a population of candidate solutions (called individuals, creatures, organisms, or phenotypes) to an optimization problem is evolved toward better solutions.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Each candidate solution has a set of properties (its chromosomes or genotype) which can be mutated and altered; traditionally, solutions are represented in binary as strings of 0s and 1s, but other encodings are also possible.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] The evolution usually starts from a population of randomly generated individuals, and is an iterative process, with the population in each iteration called a *generation*.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] In each generation, the fitness of every individual in the population is evaluated; the fitness is usually the value of the objective function in the optimization problem being solved.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] The more fit individuals are stochastically selected from the current population, and each individual's genome is modified (recombined and possibly randomly mutated) to form a new generation.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] The new generation of candidate solutions is then used in the next iteration of the algorithm.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Commonly, the algorithm terminates when either a maximum number of generations has been produced, or a satisfactory fitness level has been reached for the population.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] 2. a fitness function to evaluate the solution domain.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] A standard representation of each candidate solution is as an array of bits (also called *bit set* or *bit string*).
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Arrays of other types and structures can be used in essentially the same way.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] The main property that makes these genetic representations convenient is that their parts are easily aligned due to their fixed size, which facilitates simple crossover operations.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Variable length representations may also be used, but crossover implementation is more complex in this case.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Tree-like representations are explored in genetic programming and graph-form representations are explored in evolutionary programming; a mix of both linear chromosomes and trees is explored in gene expression programming.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Once the genetic representation and the fitness function are defined, a GA proceeds to initialize a population of solutions and then to improve it through repetitive application of the mutation, crossover, inversion and selection operators.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] The population size depends on the nature of the problem, but typically contains hundreds or thousands of possible solutions.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Often, the initial population is generated randomly, allowing the entire range of possible solutions (the search space).
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Occasionally, the solutions may be "seeded" in areas where optimal solutions are likely to be found or the distribution of the sampling probability tuned to focus in those areas of greater interest.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] During each successive generation, a portion of the existing population is selected to reproduce for a new generation.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Individual solutions are selected through a *fitness-based* process, where fitter solutions (as measured by a fitness function) are typically more likely to be selected.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Certain selection methods rate the fitness of each solution and preferentially select the best solutions.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Other methods rate only a random sample of the population, as the former process may be very time-consuming.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] The fitness function is defined over the genetic representation and measures the *quality* of the represented solution.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] The fitness function is always problem-dependent.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] For instance, in the knapsack problem one wants to maximize the total value of objects that can be put in a knapsack of some fixed capacity.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] A representation of a solution might be an array of bits, where each bit represents a different object, and the value of the bit (0 or 1) represents whether or not the object is in the knapsack.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Not every such representation is valid, as the size of objects may exceed the capacity of the knapsack.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] The *fitness* of the solution is the sum of values of all objects in the knapsack if the representation is valid, or 0 otherwise.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] The next step is to generate a second generation population of solutions from those selected, through a combination of genetic operators: crossover (also called recombination), and mutation.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] For each new solution to be produced, a pair of "parent" solutions is selected for breeding from the pool selected previously.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] By producing a "child" solution using the above methods of crossover and mutation, a new solution is created which typically shares many of the characteristics of its "parents".
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] New parents are selected for each new child, and the process continues until a new population of solutions of appropriate size is generated.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Although reproduction methods that are based on the use of two parents are more "biology inspired", some research suggests that more than two "parents" generate higher quality chromosomes.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] These processes ultimately result in the next generation population of chromosomes that is different from the initial generation.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Generally, the average fitness will have increased by this procedure for the population, since only the best organisms from the first generation are selected for breeding, along with a small proportion of less fit solutions.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] These less fit solutions ensure genetic diversity within the genetic pool of the parents and therefore ensure the genetic diversity of the subsequent generation of children.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Opinion is divided over the importance of crossover versus mutation.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] There are many references in Fogel (2006) that support the importance of mutation-based search.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] It is worth tuning parameters such as the mutation probability, crossover probability and population size to find reasonable settings for the problem's complexity class being worked on.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] A very small mutation rate may lead to genetic drift (which is non-ergodic in nature).
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] A recombination rate that is too high may lead to premature convergence of the genetic algorithm.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] A mutation rate that is too high may lead to loss of good solutions, unless elitist selection is employed.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] An adequate population size ensures sufficient genetic diversity for the problem at hand, but can lead to a waste of computational resources if set to a value larger than required.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] In addition to the main operators above, other heuristics may be employed to make the calculation faster or more robust.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] The *speciation* heuristic penalizes crossover between candidate solutions that are too similar; this encourages population diversity and helps prevent premature convergence to a less optimal solution.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] This generational process is repeated until a termination condition has been reached.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Genetic algorithms are simple to implement, but their behavior is difficult to understand.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] In particular, it is difficult to understand why these algorithms frequently succeed at generating solutions of high fitness when applied to practical problems.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] A hypothesis that a genetic algorithm performs adaptation by implicitly and efficiently implementing this heuristic.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] [crossed over], and resampled to form strings of potentially higher fitness.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] In a way, by working with these particular schemata [the building blocks], we have reduced the complexity of our problem; instead of building high-performance strings by trying every conceivable combination, we construct better and better strings from the best partial solutions of past samplings".
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] "Because highly fit schemata of low defining length and low order play such an important role in the action of genetic algorithms, we have already given them a special name: building blocks.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Despite the lack of consensus regarding the validity of the building-block hypothesis, it has been consistently evaluated and used as reference throughout the years.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Many estimation of distribution algorithms, for example, have been proposed in an attempt to provide an environment in which the hypothesis would hold.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Although good results have been reported for some classes of problems, skepticism concerning the generality and/or practicality of the building-block hypothesis as an explanation for GAs' efficiency still remains.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Indeed, there is a reasonable amount of work that attempts to understand its limitations from the perspective of estimation of distribution algorithms.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] The simplest algorithm represents each chromosome as a bit string.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Typically, numeric parameters can be represented by integers, though it is possible to use floating point representations.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] The floating point representation is natural to evolution strategies and evolutionary programming.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] The notion of real-valued genetic algorithms has been offered but is really a misnomer because it does not really represent the building block theory that was proposed by John Henry Holland in the 1970s.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] This theory is not without support though, based on theoretical and experimental results (see below).
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] The basic algorithm performs crossover and mutation at the bit level.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Other variants treat the chromosome as a list of numbers which are indexes into an instruction table, nodes in a linked list, hashes, objects, or any other imaginable data structure.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Crossover and mutation are performed so as to respect data element boundaries.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] For most data types, specific variation operators can be designed.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Different chromosomal data types seem to work better or worse for different specific problem domains.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] When bit-string representations of integers are used, Gray coding is often employed.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] In this way, small changes in the integer can be readily affected through mutations or crossovers.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] This has been found to help prevent premature convergence at so-called *Hamming walls*, in which too many simultaneous mutations (or crossover events) must occur in order to change the chromosome to a better solution.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Other approaches involve using arrays of real-valued numbers instead of bit strings to represent chromosomes.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Results from the theory of schemata suggest that in general the smaller the alphabet, the better the performance, but it was initially surprising to researchers that good results were obtained from using real-valued chromosomes.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] This was explained as the set of real values in a finite population of chromosomes as forming a *virtual alphabet* (when selection and recombination are dominant) with a much lower cardinality than would be expected from a floating point representation.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] An expansion of the Genetic Algorithm accessible problem domain can be obtained through more complex encoding of the solution pools by concatenating several types of heterogenously encoded genes into one chromosome.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] This particular approach allows for solving optimization problems that require vastly disparate definition domains for the problem parameters.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] For instance, in problems of cascaded controller tuning, the internal loop controller structure can belong to a conventional regulator of three parameters, whereas the external loop could implement a linguistic controller (such as a fuzzy system) which has an inherently different description.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] This particular form of encoding requires a specialized crossover mechanism that recombines the chromosome by section, and it is a useful tool for the modelling and simulation of complex adaptive systems, especially evolution processes.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Another important expansion of the Genetic Algorithm (GA) accessible solution space was driven by the need to make representations amenable to variable levels of knowledge about the solution states.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Variable-length representations were inspired by the observation that, in nature, evolution tends to progress from simpler organisms to more complex ones—suggesting an underlying rationale for embracing flexible structures.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] A second, more pragmatic motivation was that most real-world engineering and knowledge-based problems do not naturally conform to rigid knowledge structures.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] These early innovations in variable-length representations laid essential groundwork for the development of Genetic programming, which further extended the classical GA paradigm.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Such representations required enhancements to the simplistic genetic operators used for fixed-length chromosomes, enabling the emergence of more sophisticated and adaptive GA models.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] A practical variant of the general process of constructing a new population is to allow the best organism(s) from the current generation to carry over to the next, unaltered.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] This strategy is known as *elitist selection* and guarantees that the solution quality obtained by the GA will not decrease from one generation to the next.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Parallel implementations of genetic algorithms come in two flavors.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Coarse-grained parallel genetic algorithms assume a population on each of the computer nodes and migration of individuals among the nodes.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Fine-grained parallel genetic algorithms assume an individual on each processor node which acts with neighboring individuals for selection and reproduction.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Other variants, like genetic algorithms for online optimization problems, introduce time-dependence or noise in the fitness function.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Genetic algorithms with adaptive parameters (adaptive genetic algorithms, AGAs) is another significant and promising variant of genetic algorithms.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] The probabilities of crossover (pc) and mutation (pm) greatly determine the degree of solution accuracy and the convergence speed that genetic algorithms can obtain.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Researchers have analyzed GA convergence analytically.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Instead of using fixed values of *pc* and *pm*, AGAs utilize the population information in each generation and adaptively adjust the *pc* and *pm* in order to maintain the population diversity as well as to sustain the convergence capacity.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] In AGA (adaptive genetic algorithm), the adjustment of *pc* and *pm* depends on the fitness values of the solutions.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] There are more examples of AGA variants: Successive zooming method is an early example of improving convergence.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] In *CAGA* (clustering-based adaptive genetic algorithm), through the use of clustering analysis to judge the optimization states of the population, the adjustment of *pc* and *pm* depends on these optimization states.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Recent approaches use more abstract variables for deciding *pc* and *pm*.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Examples are dominance & co-dominance principles and LIGA (levelized interpolative genetic algorithm), which combines a flexible GA with modified A* search to tackle search space anisotropicity.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] It can be quite effective to combine GA with other optimization methods.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] A GA tends to be quite good at finding generally good global solutions, but quite inefficient at finding the last few mutations to find the absolute optimum.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Other techniques (such as simple hill climbing) are quite efficient at finding absolute optimum in a limited region.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Alternating GA and hill climbing can improve the efficiency of GA while overcoming the lack of robustness of hill climbing.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] This means that the rules of genetic variation may have a different meaning in the natural case.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] For instance – provided that steps are stored in consecutive order – crossing over may sum a number of steps from maternal DNA adding a number of steps from paternal DNA and so on.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] This is like adding vectors that more probably may follow a ridge in the phenotypic landscape.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Thus, the efficiency of the process may be increased by many orders of magnitude.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Moreover, the inversion operator has the opportunity to place steps in consecutive order or any other suitable order in favour of survival or efficiency.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] A variation, where the population as a whole is evolved rather than its individual members, is known as gene pool recombination.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] A number of variations have been developed to attempt to improve performance of GAs on problems with a high degree of fitness epistasis, i.e. where the fitness of a solution consists of interacting subsets of its variables.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Such algorithms aim to learn (before exploiting) these beneficial phenotypic interactions.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] As such, they are aligned with the Building Block Hypothesis in adaptively reducing disruptive recombination.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Prominent examples of this approach include the mGA, GEMGA and LLGA.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Problems which appear to be particularly appropriate for solution by genetic algorithms include timetabling and scheduling problems, and many scheduling software packages are based on GAs.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] GAs have also been applied to engineering.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Genetic algorithms are often applied as an approach to solve global optimization problems.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] As a general rule of thumb genetic algorithms might be useful in problem domains that have a complex fitness landscape as mixing, i.e., mutation in combination with crossover, is designed to move the population away from local optima that a traditional hill climbing algorithm might get stuck in.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Observe that commonly used crossover operators cannot change any uniform population.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Mutation alone can provide ergodicity of the overall genetic algorithm process (seen as a Markov chain).
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] In 1950, Alan Turing proposed a "learning machine" which would parallel the principles of evolution.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Computer simulation of evolution started as early as in 1954 with the work of Nils Aall Barricelli, who was using the computer at the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton, New Jersey.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] His 1954 publication was not widely noticed.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Starting in 1957, the Australian quantitative geneticist Alex Fraser published a series of papers on simulation of artificial selection of organisms with multiple loci controlling a measurable trait.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] From these beginnings, computer simulation of evolution by biologists became more common in the early 1960s, and the methods were described in books by Fraser and Burnell (1970) and Crosby (1973).
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Fraser's simulations included all of the essential elements of modern genetic algorithms.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] In addition, Hans-Joachim Bremermann published a series of papers in the 1960s that also adopted a population of solution to optimization problems, undergoing recombination, mutation, and selection.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Bremermann's research also included the elements of modern genetic algorithms.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Other noteworthy early pioneers include Richard Friedberg, George Friedman, and Michael Conrad.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Many early papers are reprinted by Fogel (1998).
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Another approach was the evolutionary programming technique of Lawrence J.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Fogel, which was proposed for generating artificial intelligence.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Evolutionary programming originally used finite state machines for predicting environments, and used variation and selection to optimize the predictive logics.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Genetic algorithms in particular became popular through the work of John Holland in the early 1970s, and particularly his book *Adaptation in Natural and Artificial Systems* (1975).
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] His work originated with studies of cellular automata, conducted by Holland and his students at the University of Michigan.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Holland introduced a formalized framework for predicting the quality of the next generation, known as Holland's Schema Theorem.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Research in GAs remained largely theoretical until the mid-1980s, when The First International Conference on Genetic Algorithms was held in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] In the late 1980s, General Electric started selling the world's first genetic algorithm product, a mainframe-based toolkit designed for industrial processes.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] In 1989, Axcelis, Inc. released Evolver,the world's first commercial GA product for desktop computers.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] The New York Times technology writer John Markoff wrote about Evolver in 1990, and it remained the only interactive commercial genetic algorithm until 1995.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Evolver was sold to Palisade in 1997, translated into several languages, and is currently in its 6th version.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Since the 1990s, MATLAB has built in three derivative-free optimization heuristic algorithms (simulated annealing, particle swarm optimization, genetic algorithm) and two direct search algorithms (simplex search, pattern search).
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Evolutionary algorithms is a sub-field of evolutionary computing.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Swarm intelligence is a sub-field of evolutionary computing.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Evolutionary computation is a sub-field of the metaheuristic methods.
[src:problem-solving/genetic-algorithm] Metaheuristic methods broadly fall within stochastic optimisation methods.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] Where finding an optimal solution is impossible or impractical, heuristic methods can be used to speed up the process of finding a satisfactory solution.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] Heuristics can be mental shortcuts that ease the cognitive load of making a decision.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] Gigerenzer & Gaissmaier (2011) state that sub-sets of *strategy* include **heuristics**, regression analysis, and Bayesian inference.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] Heuristics are strategies based on rules to generate optimal decisions, like the anchoring effect and utility maximization problem.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] These strategies depend on using readily accessible, though loosely applicable, information to control problem solving in human beings, machines and abstract issues.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] When an individual applies a heuristic in practice, it generally performs as expected.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] However it can alternatively create systematic errors.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] The most fundamental heuristic is trial and error, which can be used in everything from matching nuts and bolts to finding the values of variables in algebra problems.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] In mathematics, some common heuristics involve the use of visual representations, additional assumptions, forward/backward reasoning and simplification.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] Dual process theory concerns embodied heuristics.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] Lakatosian heuristics is based on the key term: Justification (epistemology).
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] A class whose function is to determine and filter out superfluous things.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] George Polya studied and published on heuristics in 1945.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] Polya (1945) cites Pappus of Alexandria as having written a text that Polya dubs *Heuristic*.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] Pappus' heuristic problem-solving methods consist of analysis and synthesis.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] The study of heuristics in human decision-making was developed in the 1970s and the 1980s, by the psychologists Amos Tversky and Daniel Kahneman, although the concept had been originally introduced by the Nobel laureate Herbert A.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] Simon's original primary object of research was problem solving that showed that we operate within what he calls *bounded rationality*.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] He coined the term *satisficing*, which denotes a situation in which people seek solutions, or accept choices or judgements, that are "good enough" for their purposes although they could be optimised.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] Rudolf Groner analysed the history of heuristics from its roots in ancient Greece up to contemporary work in cognitive psychology and artificial intelligence, proposing a cognitive style "heuristic versus algorithmic thinking", which can be assessed by means of a validated questionnaire.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] The *adaptive toolbox* contains strategies for fabricating heuristic devices.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] The core mental capacities are recall (memory), frequency, object permanence, and imitation.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] Gerd Gigerenzer and his research group argued that models of heuristics need to be formal to allow for predictions of behavior that can be tested.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] They study the fast and frugal heuristics in the "adaptive toolbox" of individuals or institutions, and the ecological rationality of these heuristics; that is, the conditions under which a given heuristic is likely to be successful.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] The descriptive study of the "adaptive toolbox" is done by observation and experiment, while the prescriptive study of ecological rationality requires mathematical analysis and computer simulation.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] Heuristics – such as the recognition heuristic, the take-the-best heuristic and fast-and-frugal trees – have been shown to be effective in predictions, particularly in situations of uncertainty.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] It is often said that heuristics trade accuracy for effort but this is only the case in situations of risk.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] Risk refers to situations where all possible actions, their outcomes and probabilities are known.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] In the absence of this information, that is under uncertainty, heuristics can achieve higher accuracy with lower effort.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] This finding, known as a less-is-more effect, would not have been found without formal models.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] The valuable insight of this program is that heuristics are effective not despite their simplicity – but because of it.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] Furthermore, Gigerenzer and Wolfgang Gaissmaier found that both individuals and organisations rely on heuristics in an adaptive way.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] Heuristics, through greater refinement and research, have begun to be applied to other theories, or be explained by them.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] For example, the cognitive-experiential self-theory (CEST) is also an adaptive view of heuristic processing.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] CEST breaks down two systems that process information.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] At some times, roughly speaking, individuals consider issues rationally, systematically, logically, deliberately, effortfully, and verbally.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] On other occasions, individuals consider issues intuitively, effortlessly, globally, and emotionally.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] From this perspective, heuristics are part of a larger experiential processing system that is often adaptive, but vulnerable to error in situations that require logical analysis.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] In 2002, Daniel Kahneman and Shane Frederick proposed that cognitive heuristics work by a process called *attribute substitution*, which happens without conscious awareness.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] According to this theory, when somebody makes a judgement (of a "target attribute") that is computationally complex, a more easily calculated "heuristic attribute" is substituted.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] In effect, a cognitively difficult problem is dealt with by answering a rather simpler problem, without being aware of this happening.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] This theory explains cases where judgements fail to show regression toward the mean.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] Heuristics can be considered to reduce the complexity of clinical judgments in health care.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] In psychology, heuristics are simple, efficient rules, either learned or inculcated by evolutionary processes.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] These psychological heuristics have been proposed to explain how people make decisions, come to judgements, and solve problems.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] These rules typically come into play when people face complex problems or incomplete information.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] Researchers employ various methods to test whether people use these rules.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] The rules have been shown to work well under most circumstances, but in certain cases can lead to systematic errors or cognitive biases.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] A **heuristic device** is used when an entity *X* exists to enable understanding of, or knowledge concerning, some other entity *Y*.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] A good example is a model that, as it is never identical with what it models, is a heuristic device to enable understanding of what it models.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] Stories, metaphors, etc., can also be termed heuristic in this sense.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] A classic example is the notion of utopia as described in Plato's best-known work, *The Republic*.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] This means that the "ideal city" as depicted in *The Republic* is not given as something to be pursued, or to present an orientation-point for development.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] Rather, it shows how things would have to be connected, and how one thing would lead to another (often with highly problematic results), if one opted for certain principles and carried them through rigorously.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] In legal theory, especially in the theory of law and economics, heuristics are used in the law when case-by-case analysis would be impractical, insofar as "practicality" is defined by the interests of a governing body.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] The present securities regulation regime largely assumes that all investors act as perfectly rational persons.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] In truth, actual investors face cognitive limitations from biases, heuristics, and framing effects.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] For instance, in all states in the United States the legal drinking age for unsupervised persons is 21 years, because it is argued that people need to be mature enough to make decisions involving the risks of alcohol consumption.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] However, assuming people mature at different rates, the specific age of 21 would be too late for some and too early for others.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] In this case, the somewhat arbitrary delineation is used because it is impossible or impractical to tell whether an individual is sufficiently mature for society to trust them with that kind of responsibility.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] Some proposed changes, however, have included the completion of an alcohol education course rather than the attainment of 21 years of age as the criterion for legal alcohol possession.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] This would put youth alcohol policy more on a case-by-case basis and less on a heuristic one, since the completion of such a course would presumably be voluntary and not uniform across the population.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] The same reasoning applies to patent law.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] Patents are justified on the grounds that inventors must be protected so they have incentive to invent.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] It is therefore argued that it is in society's best interest that inventors receive a temporary government-granted monopoly on their idea, so that they can recoup investment costs and make economic profit for a limited period.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] In the United States, the length of this temporary monopoly is 20 years from the date the patent application was filed, though the monopoly does not actually begin until the application has matured into a patent.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] However, like the drinking age problem above, the specific length of time would need to be different for every product to be efficient.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] A 20-year term is used because it is difficult to tell what the number should be for any individual patent.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] More recently, some, including University of North Dakota law professor Eric E.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] Johnson, have argued that patents in different kinds of industries – such as software patents – should be protected for different lengths of time.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] The bias–variance tradeoff gives insight into describing the less-is-more strategy.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] A heuristic can be used in artificial intelligence systems while searching a solution space.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] The heuristic is derived by using some function that is put into the system by the designer, or by adjusting the weight of branches based on how likely each branch is to lead to a goal node.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] Heuristics refers to the cognitive shortcuts that individuals use to simplify decision-making processes in economic situations.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] Behavioral economics is a field that integrates insights from psychology and economics to better understand how people make decisions.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] Anchoring and adjustment is one of the most extensively researched heuristics in behavioural economics.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] Anchoring is the tendency of people to make future judgements or conclusions based too heavily on the original information supplied to them.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] This initial knowledge functions as an anchor, and it can influence future judgements even if the anchor is entirely unrelated to the decisions at hand.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] Adjustment, on the other hand, is the process through which individuals make gradual changes to their initial judgements or conclusions.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] Anchoring and adjustment has been observed in a wide range of decision-making contexts, including financial decision-making, consumer behavior, and negotiation.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] Researchers have identified a number of strategies that can be used to mitigate the effects of anchoring and adjustment, including providing multiple anchors, encouraging individuals to generate alternative anchors, and providing cognitive prompts to encourage more deliberative decision-making.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] Stereotyping is a type of heuristic that people use to form opinions or make judgements about things they have never seen or experienced.
[src:problem-solving/heuristic] Stereotypes, as first described by journalist Walter Lippmann in his book *Public Opinion* (1922), are the pictures we have in our heads that are built around experiences as well as what we are told about the world.
[src:problem-solving/hill-climbing] In numerical analysis, **hill climbing** is a mathematical optimization technique which belongs to the family of local search.
[src:problem-solving/hill-climbing] It is an iterative algorithm that starts with an arbitrary solution to a problem, then attempts to find a better solution by making an incremental change to the solution.
[src:problem-solving/hill-climbing] If the change produces a better solution, another incremental change is made to the new solution, and so on until no further improvements can be found.
[src:problem-solving/hill-climbing] For example, hill climbing can be applied to the travelling salesman problem.
[src:problem-solving/hill-climbing] It is easy to find an initial solution that visits all the cities but will likely be very poor compared to the optimal solution.
[src:problem-solving/hill-climbing] The algorithm starts with such a solution and makes small improvements to it, such as switching the order in which two cities are visited.
[src:problem-solving/hill-climbing] Eventually, a much shorter route is likely to be obtained.
[src:problem-solving/hill-climbing] Examples of algorithms that solve convex problems by hill-climbing include the simplex algorithm for linear programming and binary search.
[src:problem-solving/hill-climbing] The relative simplicity of the algorithm makes it a popular first choice amongst optimizing algorithms.
[src:problem-solving/hill-climbing] It is used widely in artificial intelligence, for reaching a goal state from a starting node.
[src:problem-solving/hill-climbing] Different choices for next nodes and starting nodes are used in related algorithms.
[src:problem-solving/hill-climbing] Although more advanced algorithms such as simulated annealing or tabu search may give better results, in some situations hill climbing works just as well.
[src:problem-solving/hill-climbing] Hill climbing can often produce a better result than other algorithms when the amount of time available to perform a search is limited, such as with real-time systems, so long as a small number of increments typically converges on a good solution (the optimal solution or a close approximation).
[src:problem-solving/hill-climbing] At the other extreme, bubble sort can be viewed as a hill climbing algorithm (every adjacent element exchange decreases the number of disordered element pairs), yet this approach is far from efficient for even modest N, as the number of exchanges required grows quadratically.
[src:problem-solving/hill-climbing] Hill climbing is an anytime algorithm: it can return a valid solution even if it's interrupted at any time before it ends.
[src:problem-solving/hill-climbing] Hill climbing attempts to maximize (or minimize) a target function $f(\mathbf {x} )$ , where $\mathbf {x}$ is a vector of continuous and/or discrete values.
[src:problem-solving/hill-climbing] At each iteration, hill climbing will adjust a single element in $\mathbf {x}$ and determine whether the change improves the value of $f(\mathbf {x} )$ .
[src:problem-solving/hill-climbing] Then $\mathbf {x}$ is said to be "locally optimal".
[src:problem-solving/hill-climbing] In discrete vector spaces, each possible value for $\mathbf {x}$ may be visualized as a vertex in a graph.
[src:problem-solving/hill-climbing] Hill climbing will follow the graph from vertex to vertex, always locally increasing (or decreasing) the value of $f(\mathbf {x} )$ , until a local maximum (or local minimum) $x_{m}$ is reached.
[src:problem-solving/hill-climbing] In **simple hill climbing**, the first closer node is chosen, whereas in **steepest ascent hill climbing** all successors are compared and the closest to the solution is chosen.
[src:problem-solving/hill-climbing] Both forms fail if there is no closer node, which may happen if there are local maxima in the search space which are not solutions.
[src:problem-solving/hill-climbing] Steepest ascent hill climbing is similar to best-first search, which tries all possible extensions of the current path instead of only one.
[src:problem-solving/hill-climbing] Coordinate descent does a line search along one coordinate direction at the current point in each iteration.
[src:problem-solving/hill-climbing] Some versions of coordinate descent randomly pick a different coordinate direction each iteration.
[src:problem-solving/hill-climbing] Hill climbing will not necessarily find the global maximum, but may instead converge on a local maximum.
[src:problem-solving/hill-climbing] This problem does not occur if the heuristic is convex.
[src:problem-solving/hill-climbing] However, as many functions are not convex hill climbing may often fail to reach a global maximum.
[src:problem-solving/hill-climbing] Other local search algorithms try to overcome this problem such as stochastic hill climbing, random walks and simulated annealing.
[src:problem-solving/hill-climbing] Ridges are a challenging problem for hill climbers that optimize in continuous spaces.
[src:problem-solving/hill-climbing] Because hill climbers only adjust one element in the vector at a time, each step will move in an axis-aligned direction.
[src:problem-solving/hill-climbing] If the target function creates a narrow ridge that ascends in a non-axis-aligned direction (or if the goal is to minimize, a narrow alley that descends in a non-axis-aligned direction), then the hill climber can only ascend the ridge (or descend the alley) by zig-zagging.
[src:problem-solving/hill-climbing] If the sides of the ridge (or alley) are very steep, then the hill climber may be forced to take very tiny steps as it zig-zags toward a better position.
[src:problem-solving/hill-climbing] Thus, it may take an unreasonable length of time for it to ascend the ridge (or descend the alley).
[src:problem-solving/hill-climbing] By contrast, gradient descent methods can move in any direction that the ridge or alley may ascend or descend.
[src:problem-solving/hill-climbing] Hence, gradient descent or the conjugate gradient method is generally preferred over hill climbing when the target function is differentiable.
[src:problem-solving/hill-climbing] Hill climbers, however, have the advantage of not requiring the target function to be differentiable, so hill climbers may be preferred when the target function is complex.
[src:problem-solving/hill-climbing] Another problem that sometimes occurs with hill climbing is that of a plateau.
[src:problem-solving/hill-climbing] A plateau is encountered when the search space is flat, or sufficiently flat that the value returned by the target function is indistinguishable from the value returned for nearby regions due to the precision used by the machine to represent its value.
[src:problem-solving/hill-climbing] In such cases, the hill climber may not be able to determine in which direction it should step, and may wander in a direction that never leads to improvement.
[src:problem-solving/hill-climbing] Contrast genetic algorithm; random optimization.
[src:problem-solving/how-to-solve-it] This book has remained in print continually since 1945.
[src:problem-solving/how-to-solve-it] If this technique fails, Pólya advises: "If you cannot solve the proposed problem, try to solve first some related problem.
[src:problem-solving/how-to-solve-it] "Understand the problem" is often neglected as being obvious and is not even mentioned in many mathematics classes.
[src:problem-solving/how-to-solve-it] Yet students are often stymied in their efforts to solve it, simply because they don't understand it fully, or even in part.
[src:problem-solving/how-to-solve-it] The teacher is to select the question with the appropriate level of difficulty for each student to ascertain if each student understands at their own level, moving up or down the list to prompt each student, until each one can respond with something constructive.
[src:problem-solving/how-to-solve-it] Pólya mentions that there are many reasonable ways to solve problems.
[src:problem-solving/how-to-solve-it] The skill at choosing an appropriate strategy is best learned by solving many problems.
[src:problem-solving/how-to-solve-it] You will find choosing a strategy increasingly easy.
[src:problem-solving/how-to-solve-it] Pólya lays a big emphasis on the teachers' behavior.
[src:problem-solving/how-to-solve-it] A teacher should support students with devising their own plan with a question method that goes from the most general questions to more particular questions, with the goal that the last step to having a plan is made by the student.
[src:problem-solving/how-to-solve-it] He maintains that just showing students a plan, no matter how good it is, does not help them.
[src:problem-solving/how-to-solve-it] This step is usually easier than devising the plan.
[src:problem-solving/how-to-solve-it] In general, all you need is care and patience, given that you have the necessary skills.
[src:problem-solving/how-to-solve-it] Persist with the plan that you have chosen.
[src:problem-solving/how-to-solve-it] If it continues not to work, discard it and choose another.
[src:problem-solving/how-to-solve-it] Don't be misled; this is how mathematics is done, even by professionals.
[src:problem-solving/how-to-solve-it] Pólya mentions that much can be gained by taking the time to reflect and look back at what you have done, what worked and what did not, and with thinking about other problems where this could be useful.
[src:problem-solving/how-to-solve-it] Doing this will enable you to predict what strategy to use to solve future problems, if these relate to the original problem.
[src:problem-solving/how-to-solve-it] The book contains a dictionary-style set of heuristics, many of which have to do with generating a more accessible problem.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] The **maximin value** is the highest value that the player can be sure to get without knowing the actions of the other players; equivalently, it is the lowest value the other players can force the player to receive when they know the player's action.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] Calculating the maximin value of a player is done in a worst-case approach: for each possible action of the player, we check all possible actions of the other players and determine the worst possible combination of actions – the one that gives player i the smallest value.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] Then, we determine which action player i can take in order to make sure that this smallest value is the highest possible.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] For example, consider the following game for two players, where the first player ("row player") may choose any of three moves, labelled T, M, or B, and the second player ("column player") may choose either of two moves, L or R.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] (where the first number in each of the cell is the pay-out of the row player and the second number is the pay-out of the column player).
[src:problem-solving/minimax] For the sake of example, we consider only pure strategies.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] If both players play their respective maximin strategies $(T,L)$ , the payoff vector is $(3,1)$ .
[src:problem-solving/minimax] The **minimax value** of a player is the smallest value that the other players can force the player to receive, without knowing the player's actions; equivalently, it is the largest value the player can be sure to get when they *know* the actions of the other players.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] The definition is very similar to that of the maximin value – only the order of the maximum and minimum operators is inverse.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] In two-player zero-sum games, the minimax solution is the same as the Nash equilibrium.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] Equivalently, Player 1's strategy guarantees them a payoff of V regardless of Player 2's strategy, and similarly Player 2 can guarantee themselves a payoff of −V.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] The name *minimax* arises because each player minimizes the maximum payoff possible for the other – since the game is zero-sum, they also minimize their own maximum loss (i.e., maximize their minimum payoff).
[src:problem-solving/minimax] See also example of a game without a value.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] The following example of a zero-sum game, where **A** and **B** make simultaneous moves, illustrates *maximin* solutions.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] Suppose each player has three choices and consider the payoff matrix for **A** displayed on the table ("Payoff matrix for player A").
[src:problem-solving/minimax] Assume the payoff matrix for **B** is the same matrix with the signs reversed (i.e., if the choices are A1 and B1 then **B** pays 3 to **A**).
[src:problem-solving/minimax] Then, the maximin choice for **A** is A2 since the worst possible result is then having to pay 1, while the simple maximin choice for **B** is B2 since the worst possible result is then no payment.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] Some choices are *dominated* by others and can be eliminated: **A** will not choose A3 since either A1 or A2 will produce a better result, no matter what **B** chooses; **B** will not choose B3 since some mixtures of B1 and B2 will produce a better result, no matter what **A** chooses.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] Similarly, **B** can ensure an expected gain of at least ⁠1/ 3 ⁠, no matter what **A** chooses, by using a randomized strategy of choosing B1 with probability ⁠1/ 3 ⁠ and B2 with probability ⁠2/ 3 ⁠.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] These mixed minimax strategies cannot be improved and are now stable.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] Frequently, in game theory, **maximin** is distinct from minimax.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] Minimax is used in zero-sum games to denote minimizing the opponent's maximum payoff.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] In a zero-sum game, this is identical to minimizing one's own maximum loss, and to maximizing one's own minimum gain.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] "Maximin" is a term commonly used for non-zero-sum games to describe the strategy which maximizes one's own minimum payoff.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] In non-zero-sum games, this is not generally the same as minimizing the opponent's maximum gain, nor the same as the Nash equilibrium strategy.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] The minimax values are very important in the theory of repeated games.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] One of the central theorems in this theory, the folk theorem, relies on the minimax values.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] In combinatorial game theory, there is a minimax algorithm for game solutions.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] A **simple** version of the minimax *algorithm*, stated below, deals with games such as tic-tac-toe, where each player can win, lose, or draw.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] If player A *can* win in one move, their best move is that winning move.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] If player B knows that one move will lead to the situation where player A *can* win in one move, while another move will lead to the situation where player A can, at best, draw, then player B's best move is the one leading to a draw.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] Late in the game, it's easy to see what the "best" move is.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] The minimax algorithm helps find the best move, by working backwards from the end of the game.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] At each step it assumes that player A is trying to **maximize** the chances of A winning, while on the next turn player B is trying to **minimize** the chances of A winning (i.e., to maximize B's own chances of winning).
[src:problem-solving/minimax] A **minimax algorithm** is a recursive algorithm for choosing the next move in an n-player game, usually a two-player game.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] A value is associated with each position or state of the game.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] This value is computed by means of a position evaluation function and it indicates how good it would be for a player to reach that position.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] The player then makes the move that maximizes the minimum value of the position resulting from the opponent's possible following moves.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] If it is **A**'s turn to move, **A** gives a value to each of their legal moves.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] A possible allocation method consists in assigning a certain win for **A** as +1 and for **B** as −1.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] This leads to combinatorial game theory as developed by John H.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] An alternative is using a rule that if the result of a move is an immediate win for **A**, it is assigned positive infinity and if it is an immediate win for **B**, negative infinity.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] The value to **A** of any other move is the maximum of the values resulting from each of **B**'s possible replies.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] For this reason, **A** is called the *maximizing player* and **B** is called the *minimizing player*, hence the name *minimax algorithm*.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] The above algorithm will assign a value of positive or negative infinity to any position since the value of every position will be the value of some final winning or losing position.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] This can be extended if we can supply a heuristic evaluation function which gives values to non-final game states without considering all possible following complete sequences.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] We can then limit the minimax algorithm to look only at a certain number of moves ahead.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] This number is called the "look-ahead", measured in "plies".
[src:problem-solving/minimax] For example, the chess computer Deep Blue (the first one to beat a reigning world champion, Garry Kasparov at that time) looked ahead at least 12 plies, then applied a heuristic evaluation function.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] The algorithm can be thought of as exploring the nodes of a *game tree*.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] The *effective branching factor* of the tree is the average number of children of each node (i.e., the average number of legal moves in a position).
[src:problem-solving/minimax] The number of nodes to be explored usually increases exponentially with the number of plies (it is less than exponential if evaluating forced moves or repeated positions).
[src:problem-solving/minimax] The number of nodes to be explored for the analysis of a game is therefore approximately the branching factor raised to the power of the number of plies.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] It is therefore impractical to completely analyze games such as chess using the minimax algorithm.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] The performance of the naïve minimax algorithm may be improved dramatically, without affecting the result, by the use of alpha–beta pruning.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] Other heuristic pruning methods can also be used, but not all of them are guaranteed to give the same result as the unpruned search.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] A naïve minimax algorithm may be trivially modified to additionally return an entire Principal Variation along with a minimax score.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] The pseudocode for the depth-limited minimax algorithm is given below.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] The minimax function returns a heuristic value for leaf nodes (terminal nodes and nodes at the maximum search depth).
[src:problem-solving/minimax] Non-leaf nodes inherit their value from a descendant leaf node.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] The heuristic value is a score measuring the favorability of the node for the maximizing player.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] Hence nodes resulting in a favorable outcome, such as a win, for the maximizing player have higher scores than nodes more favorable for the minimizing player.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] The heuristic value for terminal (game ending) leaf nodes are scores corresponding to win, loss, or draw, for the maximizing player.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] For non terminal leaf nodes at the maximum search depth, an evaluation function estimates a heuristic value for the node.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] The quality of this estimate and the search depth determine the quality and accuracy of the final minimax result.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] Minimax treats the two players (the maximizing player and the minimizing player) separately in its code.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] Based on the observation that $\ \max(a,b)=-\min(-a,-b)\ ,$ minimax may often be simplified into the negamax algorithm.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] Suppose the game being played only has a maximum of two possible moves per player each turn.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] The algorithm generates the tree on the right, where the circles represent the moves of the player running the algorithm (*maximizing player*), and squares represent the moves of the opponent (*minimizing player*).
[src:problem-solving/minimax] Because of the limitation of computation resources, as explained above, the tree is limited to a *look-ahead* of 4 moves.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] The algorithm evaluates each *leaf node* using a heuristic evaluation function, obtaining the values shown.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] The moves where the *maximizing player* wins are assigned with positive infinity, while the moves that lead to a win of the *minimizing player* are assigned with negative infinity.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] At level 3, the algorithm will choose, for each node, the **smallest** of the *child node* values, and assign it to that same node (e.g. the node on the left will choose the minimum between "10" and "+∞", therefore assigning the value "10" to itself).
[src:problem-solving/minimax] The next step, in level 2, consists of choosing for each node the **largest** of the *child node* values.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] Once again, the values are assigned to each *parent node*.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] The algorithm continues evaluating the maximum and minimum values of the child nodes alternately until it reaches the *root node*, where it chooses the move with the largest value (represented in the figure with a blue arrow).
[src:problem-solving/minimax] This is the move that the player should make in order to *minimize* the *maximum* possible loss.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] Minimax theory has been extended to decisions where there is no other player, but where the consequences of decisions depend on unknown facts.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] For example, deciding to prospect for minerals entails a cost, which will be wasted if the minerals are not present, but will bring major rewards if they are.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] One approach is to treat this as a game against *nature* (see move by nature), and using a similar mindset as Murphy's law or resistentialism, take an approach which minimizes the maximum expected loss, using the same techniques as in the two-person zero-sum games.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] In addition, expectiminimax trees have been developed, for two-player games in which chance (for example, dice) is a factor.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] In classical statistical decision theory, we have an estimator $\ \delta \$ that is used to estimate a parameter $\ \theta \in \Theta \ .$ We also assume a risk function $\ R(\theta ,\delta )\ .$ usually specified as the integral of a loss function.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] A key feature of minimax decision making is being non-probabilistic: in contrast to decisions using expected value or expected utility, it makes no assumptions about the probabilities of various outcomes, just scenario analysis of what the possible outcomes are.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] It is thus robust to changes in the assumptions, in contrast to these other decision techniques.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] Various extensions of this non-probabilistic approach exist, notably minimax regret and Info-gap decision theory.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] Compare to expected value analysis, whose conclusion is of the form: "This strategy yields ℰ(X) = n ." Minimax thus can be used on ordinal data, and can be more transparent.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] In philosophy, the term "maximin" is often used in the context of John Rawls's *A Theory of Justice,* where he refers to it in the context of The Difference Principle.
[src:problem-solving/minimax] Rawls defined this principle as the rule which states that social and economic inequalities should be arranged so that "they are to be of the greatest benefit to the least-advantaged members of society".
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Solutions require sufficient resources and knowledge to attain the goal.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Professionals such as lawyers, doctors, programmers, and consultants are largely problem solvers for issues that require technical skills and knowledge beyond general competence.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Many businesses have found profitable markets by recognizing a problem and creating a solution: the more widespread and inconvenient the problem, the greater the opportunity to develop a scalable solution.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] There are many specialized problem-solving techniques and methods in fields such as science, engineering, business, medicine, mathematics, computer science, philosophy, and social organization.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] The mental techniques to identify, analyze, and solve problems are studied in psychology and cognitive sciences.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Also widely researched are the mental obstacles that prevent people from finding solutions; problem-solving impediments include confirmation bias, mental set, and functional fixedness.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] The term *problem solving* has a slightly different meaning depending on the discipline.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] For instance, it is a mental process in psychology and a computerized process in computer science.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] There are two different types of problems: ill-defined and well-defined; different approaches are used for each.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Well-defined problems have specific end goals and clearly expected solutions, while ill-defined problems do not.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Well-defined problems allow for more initial planning than ill-defined problems.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Solving problems sometimes involves dealing with pragmatics (the way that context contributes to meaning) and semantics (the interpretation of the problem).
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] The ability to understand what the end goal of the problem is, and what rules could be applied, represents the key to solving the problem.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Sometimes a problem requires abstract thinking or coming up with a creative solution.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Problem solving has two major domains: mathematical problem solving and personal problem solving.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Each concerns some difficulty or barrier that is encountered.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Problem solving in psychology refers to the process of finding solutions to problems encountered in life.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Solutions to these problems are usually situation- or context-specific.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] The process starts with problem finding, in which the problem is discovered and simplified.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] The next step is to generate possible solutions and evaluate them.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Finally a solution is selected to be implemented and verified.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Problems have an *end goal* to be reached; how you get there depends upon problem orientation (problem-solving coping style and skills) and systematic analysis.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Mental health professionals study the human problem-solving processes using methods such as introspection, behaviorism, simulation, computer modeling, and experiment.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Social psychologists look into the person-environment relationship aspect of the problem and independent and interdependent problem-solving methods.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Problem solving has been defined as a higher-order cognitive process and intellectual function that requires the modulation and control of more routine or fundamental skills.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Empirical research shows many different strategies and factors influence everyday problem solving.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Rehabilitation psychologists studying people with frontal lobe injuries have found that deficits in emotional control and reasoning can be re-mediated with effective rehabilitation and could improve the capacity of injured persons to resolve everyday problems.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Interpersonal everyday problem solving is dependent upon personal motivational and contextual components.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] One such component is the emotional valence of "real-world" problems, which can either impede or aid problem-solving performance.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Researchers have focused on the role of emotions in problem solving, demonstrating that poor emotional control can disrupt focus on the target task, impede problem resolution, and lead to negative outcomes such as fatigue, depression, and inertia.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] In conceptualization,human problem solving consists of two related processes: problem orientation, and the motivational/attitudinal/affective approach to problematic situations and problem-solving skills.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] People's strategies cohere with their goals and stem from the process of comparing oneself with others.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Among the first experimental psychologists to study problem solving were the Gestaltists in Germany, such as Karl Duncker in *The Psychology of Productive Thinking* (1935).
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Perhaps best known is the work of Allen Newell and Herbert A.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Experiments in the 1960s and early 1970s asked participants to solve relatively simple, well-defined, but not previously seen laboratory tasks.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] These simple problems, such as the Tower of Hanoi, admitted optimal solutions that could be found quickly, allowing researchers to observe the full problem-solving process.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Researchers assumed that these model problems would elicit the characteristic cognitive processes by which more complex "real world" problems are solved.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] An outstanding problem-solving technique found by this research is the principle of decomposition.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Much of computer science and artificial intelligence involves designing automated systems to solve a specified type of problem: to accept input data and calculate a correct or adequate response, reasonably quickly.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Algorithms are recipes or instructions that direct such systems, written into computer programs.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Steps for designing such systems include problem determination, heuristics, root cause analysis, de-duplication, analysis, diagnosis, and repair.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Analytic techniques include linear and nonlinear programming, queuing systems, and simulation.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] A large, perennial obstacle is to find and fix errors in computer programs: debugging.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Formal logic concerns issues like validity, truth, inference, argumentation, and proof.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] In a problem-solving context, it can be used to formally represent a problem as a theorem to be proved, and to represent the knowledge needed to solve the problem as the premises to be used in a proof that the problem has a solution.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] The use of computers to prove mathematical theorems using formal logic emerged as the field of automated theorem proving in the 1950s.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] It included the use of heuristic methods designed to simulate human problem solving, as in the Logic Theory Machine, developed by Allen Newell, Herbert A.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Shaw, as well as algorithmic methods such as the resolution principle developed by John Alan Robinson.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] In addition to its use for finding proofs of mathematical theorems, automated theorem-proving has also been used for program verification in computer science.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] In 1958, John McCarthy proposed the advice taker, to represent information in formal logic and to derive answers to questions using automated theorem-proving.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] An important step in this direction was made by Cordell Green in 1969, who used a resolution theorem prover for question-answering and for such other applications in artificial intelligence as robot planning.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] The resolution theorem-prover used by Cordell Green bore little resemblance to human problem solving methods.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] In response to criticism of that approach from researchers at MIT, Robert Kowalski developed logic programming and SLD resolution, which solves problems by problem decomposition.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] He has advocated logic for both computer and human problem solving and computational logic to improve human thinking.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] When products or processes fail, problem solving techniques can be used to develop corrective actions that can be taken to prevent further failures.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Such techniques can also be applied to a product or process prior to an actual failure event—to predict, analyze, and mitigate a potential problem in advance.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Techniques such as failure mode and effects analysis can proactively reduce the likelihood of problems.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] In either the reactive or the proactive case, it is necessary to build a causal explanation through a process of diagnosis.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] In deriving an explanation of effects in terms of causes, abduction generates new ideas or hypotheses (asking "how?"); deduction evaluates and refines hypotheses based on other plausible premises (asking "why?"); and induction justifies a hypothesis with empirical data (asking "how much?").
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] The objective of abduction is to determine which hypothesis or proposition to test, not which one to adopt or assert.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] In the Peircean logical system, the logic of abduction and deduction contribute to our conceptual understanding of a phenomenon, while the logic of induction adds quantitative details (empirical substantiation) to our conceptual knowledge.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Forensic engineering is an important technique of failure analysis that involves tracing product defects and flaws.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Corrective action can then be taken to prevent further failures.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Reverse engineering attempts to discover the original problem-solving logic used in developing a product by disassembling the product and developing a plausible pathway to creating and assembling its parts.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] In physics, problem solving refers to the process by which one transforms an initial physical situation into a goal state by applying physics-specific reasoning and analysis.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] This involves identifying the relevant physical principles, making assumptions, formulating and manipulating equations, and checking whether the results are reasonable.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] A physics problem is not simply the application or recall of a formula, but requires understanding the underlying concepts and navigating through a “problem space” of possible knowledge states toward the goal.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] In military science, problem solving is linked to the concept of "end-states", the conditions or situations which are the aims of the strategy.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Ability to solve problems is important at any military rank, but is essential at the command and control level.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] It results from deep qualitative and quantitative understanding of possible scenarios.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] *Effectiveness* in this context is an evaluation of results: to what extent the end states were accomplished.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] *Planning* is the process of determining how to effect those end states.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Some models of problem solving involve identifying a goal and then a sequence of subgoals towards achieving this goal.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Andersson, who introduced the ACT-R model of cognition, modelled this collection of goals and subgoals as a goal stack in which the mind contains a stack of goals and subgoals to be completed, and a single task being carried out at any time.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Knowledge of how to solve one problem can be applied to another problem, in a process known as transfer.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Problem-solving strategies are steps to overcoming the obstacles to achieving a goal.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] The iteration of such strategies over the course of solving a problem is the "problem-solving cycle".
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Common steps in this cycle include recognizing the problem, defining it, developing a strategy to solve it, organizing available knowledge and resources, monitoring progress, and evaluating the effectiveness of the solution.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Once a solution is achieved, another problem usually arises, and the cycle starts again.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Insight is the sudden a*ha!* solution to a problem, the birth of a new idea to simplify a complex situation.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Solutions found through insight are often more incisive than those from step-by-step analysis.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] A quick solution process requires insight to select productive moves at different stages of the problem-solving cycle.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Unlike Newell and Simon's formal definition of a *move problem*, there is no consensus definition of an *insight problem*.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] transform the problem into another problem that is easier to solve, bypassing the barrier, then transform that solution back to a solution to the original problem.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] try to prove that the problem cannot be solved.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Common barriers to problem solving include mental constructs that impede an efficient search for solutions.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Five of the most common identified by researchers are: confirmation bias, mental set, functional fixedness, unnecessary constraints, and irrelevant information.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Confirmation bias is an unintentional tendency to collect and use data which favors preconceived notions.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Such notions may be incidental rather than motivated by important personal beliefs: the desire to be right may be sufficient motivation.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Scientific and technical professionals also experience confirmation bias.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] One online experiment, for example, suggested that professionals within the field of psychological research are likely to view scientific studies that agree with their preconceived notions more favorably than clashing studies.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] According to Raymond Nickerson, one can see the consequences of confirmation bias in real-life situations, which range in severity from inefficient government policies to genocide.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Nickerson argued that those who killed people accused of witchcraft demonstrated confirmation bias with motivation.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Researcher Michael Allen found evidence for confirmation bias with motivation in school children who worked to manipulate their science experiments to produce favorable results.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] However, confirmation bias does not necessarily require motivation.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] In 1960, Peter Cathcart Wason conducted an experiment in which participants first viewed three numbers and then created a hypothesis in the form of a rule that could have been used to create that triplet of numbers.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] When testing their hypotheses, participants tended to only create additional triplets of numbers that would confirm their hypotheses, and tended not to create triplets that would negate or disprove their hypotheses.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Mental set is the inclination to re-use a previously successful solution, rather than search for new and better solutions.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Luchins in the 1940s with his well-known water jug experiments.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Participants were asked to fill one jug with a specific amount of water by using other jugs with different maximum capacities.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] After Luchins gave a set of jug problems that could all be solved by a single technique, he then introduced a problem that could be solved by the same technique, but also by a novel and simpler method.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] His participants tended to use the accustomed technique, oblivious of the simpler alternative.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] This was again demonstrated in Norman Maier's 1931 experiment, which challenged participants to solve a problem by using a familiar tool (pliers) in an unconventional manner.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Participants were often unable to view the object in a way that strayed from its typical use, a type of mental set known as functional fixedness (see the following section).
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Rigidly clinging to a mental set is called *fixation*, which can deepen to an obsession or preoccupation with attempted strategies that are repeatedly unsuccessful.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] In the late 1990s, researcher Jennifer Wiley found that professional expertise in a field can create a mental set, perhaps leading to fixation.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Groupthink, in which each individual takes on the mindset of the rest of the group, can produce and exacerbate mental set.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Social pressure leads to everybody thinking the same thing and reaching the same conclusions.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Functional fixedness is the tendency to view an object as having only one function, and to be unable to conceive of any novel use, as in the Maier pliers experiment described above.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Functional fixedness is a specific form of mental set, and is one of the most common forms of cognitive bias in daily life.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] As an example, imagine a man wants to kill a bug in his house, but the only thing at hand is a can of air freshener.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] He may start searching for something to kill the bug instead of squashing it with the can, thinking only of its main function of deodorizing.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] There are several hypotheses in regards to how functional fixedness relates to problem solving.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] It may waste time, delaying or entirely preventing the correct use of a tool.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Unnecessary constraints are arbitrary boundaries imposed unconsciously on the task at hand, which foreclose a productive avenue of solution.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] The solver may become fixated on only one type of solution, as if it were an inevitable requirement of the problem.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Typically, this combines with mental set—clinging to a previously successful method.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Visual problems can also produce mentally invented constraints.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] A famous example is the dot problem: nine dots arranged in a three-by-three grid pattern must be connected by drawing four straight line segments, without lifting pen from paper or backtracking along a line.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] The subject typically assumes the pen must stay within the outer square of dots, but the solution requires lines continuing beyond this frame, and researchers have found a 0% solution rate within a brief allotted time.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] This problem has produced the expression "think outside the box".
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Such problems are typically solved via a sudden insight which leaps over the mental barriers, often after long toil against them.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] This can be difficult depending on how the subject has structured the problem in their mind, how they draw on past experiences, and how well they juggle this information in their working memory.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] In the example, envisioning the dots connected outside the framing square requires visualizing an unconventional arrangement, which is a strain on working memory.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Irrelevant information is a specification or data presented in a problem that is unrelated to the solution.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] If the solver assumes that all information presented needs to be used, this often derails the problem solving process, making relatively simple problems much harder.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] For example: "Fifteen percent of the people in Topeka have unlisted telephone numbers.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] You select 200 names at random from the Topeka phone book.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] How many of these people have unlisted phone numbers?" The "obvious" answer is 15%, but in fact none of the unlisted people would be listed among the 200.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] This kind of "trick question" is often used in aptitude tests or cognitive evaluations.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Though not inherently difficult, they require independent thinking that is not necessarily common.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Mathematical word problems often include irrelevant qualitative or numerical information as an extra challenge.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] The disruption caused by the above cognitive biases can depend on how the information is represented: visually, verbally, or mathematically.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] The problem cannot be addressed in a verbal context, trying to describe the monk's progress on each day.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] It becomes much easier when the paragraph is represented mathematically by a function: one visualizes a graph whose horizontal axis is time of day, and whose vertical axis shows the monk's position (or altitude) on the path at each time.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Superimposing the two journey curves, which traverse opposite diagonals of a rectangle, one sees they must cross each other somewhere.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] The visual representation by graphing has resolved the difficulty.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Similar strategies can often improve problem solving on tests.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] People who are engaged in problem solving tend to overlook subtractive changes, even those that are critical elements of efficient solutions.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] For example, a city planner may decide that the solution to decrease traffic congestion would be to add another lane to a highway, rather than finding ways to reduce the need for the highway in the first place.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] This tendency to solve by first, only, or mostly creating or adding elements, rather than by subtracting elements or processes is shown to intensify with higher cognitive loads such as information overload.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] People can also solve problems while they are asleep.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] There are many reports of scientists and engineers who solved problems in their dreams.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] For example, Elias Howe, inventor of the sewing machine, figured out the structure of the bobbin from a dream.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] The chemist August Kekulé was considering how benzene arranged its six carbon and hydrogen atoms.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Thinking about the problem, he dozed off, and dreamt of dancing atoms that fell into a snakelike pattern, which led him to discover the benzene ring.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] There also are empirical studies of how people can think consciously about a problem before going to sleep, and then solve the problem with a dream image.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Dement told his undergraduate class of 500 students that he wanted them to think about an infinite series, whose first elements were OTTFF, to see if they could deduce the principle behind it and to say what the next elements of the series would be.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] He asked them to think about this problem every night for 15 minutes before going to sleep and to write down any dreams that they then had.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] They were instructed to think about the problem again for 15 minutes when they awakened in the morning.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] The sequence OTTFF is the first letters of the numbers: one, two, three, four, five.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] The next five elements of the series are SSENT (six, seven, eight, nine, ten).
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Some of the students solved the puzzle by reflecting on their dreams.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] With more than 500 undergraduate students, 87 dreams were judged to be related to the problems students were assigned (53 directly related and 34 indirectly related).
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Yet of the people who had dreams that apparently solved the problem, only seven were actually able to consciously know the solution.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] The rest (46 out of 53) thought they did not know the solution.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Albert Einstein believed that much problem solving goes on unconsciously, and the person must then figure out and formulate consciously what the mindbrain has already solved.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] He believed this was his process in formulating the theory of relativity: "The creator of the problem possesses the solution." Einstein said that he did his problem solving without words, mostly in images.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] "The words or the language, as they are written or spoken, do not seem to play any role in my mechanism of thought.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Problem-solving processes differ across knowledge domains and across levels of expertise.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] For this reason, cognitive sciences findings obtained in the laboratory cannot necessarily generalize to problem-solving situations outside the laboratory.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] This has led to a research emphasis on real-world problem solving, since the 1990s.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] This emphasis has been expressed quite differently in North America and Europe, however.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Whereas North American research has typically concentrated on studying problem solving in separate, natural knowledge domains, much of the European research has focused on novel, complex problems, and has been performed with computerized scenarios.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] In Europe, two main approaches have surfaced, one initiated by Donald Broadbent in the United Kingdom and the other one by Dietrich Dörner in Germany.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] The two approaches share an emphasis on relatively complex, semantically rich, computerized laboratory tasks, constructed to resemble real-life problems.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] The approaches differ somewhat in their theoretical goals and methodology.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] The tradition initiated by Broadbent emphasizes the distinction between cognitive problem-solving processes that operate under awareness versus outside of awareness, and typically employs mathematically well-defined computerized systems.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] The tradition initiated by Dörner, on the other hand, has an interest in the interplay of the cognitive, motivational, and social components of problem solving, and utilizes very complex computerized scenarios that contain up to 2,000 highly interconnected variables.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] In North America, initiated by the work of Herbert A.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Simon on "learning by doing" in semantically rich domains, researchers began to investigate problem solving separately in different natural knowledge domains—such as physics, writing, or chess playing—rather than attempt to extract a global theory of problem solving.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] These researchers have focused on the development of problem solving within certain domains, that is on the development of expertise.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Complex problem solving (CPS) is distinguishable from simple problem solving (SPS).
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] In SPS there is a singular and simple obstacle.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] In CPS there may be multiple simultaneous obstacles.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] For example, a surgeon at work has far more complex problems than an individual deciding what shoes to wear.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] People solve problems on many different levels—from the individual to the civilizational.
[src:problem-solving/problem-solving] Collective problem solving refers to problem solving performed collectively.
